1
00:02:03,127 --> 00:02:04,879
Can I help you, ma'am?

2
00:02:05,527 --> 00:02:08,997
Well, they told me to take
a streetcar named Desire...

3
00:02:09,167 --> 00:02:11,556
...and then transfer
to one called Cemeteries...

4
00:02:11,727 --> 00:02:15,606
...and ride six blocks
and get off at Elysian Fields.

5
00:02:15,767 --> 00:02:16,882
There's your car now.

6
00:02:27,367 --> 00:02:28,880
Thank you.

7
00:03:05,007 --> 00:03:07,043
When he got home, she was waiting.

8
00:03:07,207 --> 00:03:09,960
Boy, you never heard nothing like that.

9
00:03:15,607 --> 00:03:17,325
What's the matter, honey?
You lost?

10
00:03:17,487 --> 00:03:19,478
I'm looking for Elysian Fields.

11
00:03:19,647 --> 00:03:22,161
This is Elysian Fields.
What number you looking for?

12
00:03:22,407 --> 00:03:24,125
Six forty-two.

13
00:03:24,287 --> 00:03:26,482
You don't need to look no further.

14
00:03:27,127 --> 00:03:31,200
I'm looking for my sister, Stella DuBois.
I mean, Mrs. Stanley Kowalski.

15
00:03:31,407 --> 00:03:35,525
Yeah, that's the party, all right.
You just did miss her, though.

16
00:03:35,927 --> 00:03:37,360
Yes?

17
00:03:38,447 --> 00:03:42,599
- Can this be her home?
- She got the downstairs. I got the up.

18
00:03:42,767 --> 00:03:44,723
Oh, she's out?

19
00:03:44,887 --> 00:03:47,117
You notice that bowling alley
up the street?

20
00:03:47,287 --> 00:03:49,801
- I'm not sure I did.
- Well, that's where she's at, honey.

21
00:03:49,967 --> 00:03:52,003
She's watching her husband bowl.

22
00:04:01,567 --> 00:04:03,205
Blanche!

23
00:04:06,447 --> 00:04:08,085
Blanche, honey!

24
00:04:08,367 --> 00:04:11,677
- Stella. Oh, Stella for star!
- Blanche!

25
00:04:11,847 --> 00:04:15,965
Oh, my darling. Now, let me look at you.
But don't you look at me, Stella. No, no!

26
00:04:16,127 --> 00:04:19,164
- I won't be seen in this merciless glare.
- Did you find our place?

27
00:04:19,327 --> 00:04:21,079
What are you doing in a place like that?

28
00:04:21,247 --> 00:04:23,761
Never, never, never
in my worst dreams did I picture...

29
00:04:23,927 --> 00:04:27,363
Only Poe. Only Mr. Edgar Allan Poe
could do justice to it.

30
00:04:27,527 --> 00:04:29,404
What are you doing
in that horrible place?

31
00:04:29,567 --> 00:04:31,637
Oh, what am I saying?
I didn't mean to say that.

32
00:04:31,807 --> 00:04:34,924
I meant to be nice and say,
"What a convenient location," and such.

33
00:04:35,087 --> 00:04:37,920
- You haven't said a word to me.
- You haven't given me a chance to.

34
00:04:38,087 --> 00:04:41,477
- Open your pretty mouth and talk.
- Come say hello to Stanley first.

35
00:04:41,647 --> 00:04:43,922
- No, not now. Not now.
- Just say hello.

36
00:04:44,087 --> 00:04:47,124
Oh, which is he?
Which one is he?

37
00:04:52,287 --> 00:04:55,916
- Is he the one that's...
- The one that's making all the rhubarb.

38
00:04:56,087 --> 00:04:58,237
Isn't he wonderful-looking?

39
00:05:03,167 --> 00:05:06,716
Stella, I can't meet him now.
Not till I've bathed and rested.

40
00:05:06,887 --> 00:05:10,323
- Would you like a cold drink?
- Oh, bless you for that lovely inspiration.

41
00:05:14,887 --> 00:05:17,037
Oh, my baby, my baby.

42
00:05:18,367 --> 00:05:19,766
Would you like some pop?

43
00:05:19,927 --> 00:05:22,043
Honey. Pop?

44
00:05:22,207 --> 00:05:24,437
Not with my nerves tonight.
Scotch for me, please.

45
00:05:24,607 --> 00:05:26,165
Grape.

46
00:05:26,327 --> 00:05:31,242
You haven't asked me how I got away
from school before the spring term ended.

47
00:05:31,407 --> 00:05:34,843
I thought you'd volunteer that
information if you want to tell me.

48
00:05:35,007 --> 00:05:39,125
- You thought I'd been fired?
- No. I thought you might have resigned.

49
00:05:39,287 --> 00:05:43,485
Oh, I was so exhausted
by all I'd been through, my nerves broke.

50
00:05:44,887 --> 00:05:47,560
I was on the verge of lunacy, almost.

51
00:05:47,727 --> 00:05:48,921
So Mr. Graves...

52
00:05:49,087 --> 00:05:50,998
Mr. Graves is the high school
superintendent.

53
00:05:51,167 --> 00:05:52,725
Thank you. He suggested l...

54
00:05:54,207 --> 00:05:55,606
I take a leave of absence.

55
00:05:55,767 --> 00:05:57,758
I couldn't put all those
details into the wire.

56
00:05:57,927 --> 00:05:59,918
This buzzes right through me
and feels so good.

57
00:06:00,087 --> 00:06:02,920
- Would you like another?
- One's my limit.

58
00:06:03,087 --> 00:06:04,918
You haven't said a word
about my appearance.

59
00:06:05,087 --> 00:06:07,840
- You look just fine.
- God love you for a liar.

60
00:06:08,007 --> 00:06:10,475
Daylight never exposed so total a ruin.

61
00:06:10,647 --> 00:06:12,797
But you...
You put on some weight. Yes.

62
00:06:12,967 --> 00:06:16,277
You're just as plump as a little partridge.
It's so becoming to you too.

63
00:06:16,447 --> 00:06:19,439
- Oh, Blanche.
- Yes, it is. Or I wouldn't say it. You...

64
00:06:19,607 --> 00:06:22,326
...just have to
watch around the hips a little.

65
00:06:22,487 --> 00:06:24,239
I want you to look at my
figure, you know?

66
00:06:24,407 --> 00:06:26,398
I haven't put on one ounce
in 10 years, Stella.

67
00:06:26,567 --> 00:06:29,559
I weigh now what I weighed
the summer you left Belle Reve.

68
00:06:29,727 --> 00:06:31,604
The summer Dad died...

69
00:06:31,767 --> 00:06:33,519
...and you left us.

70
00:06:38,487 --> 00:06:41,877
It's just incredible, Blanche,
how well you look.

71
00:06:44,687 --> 00:06:47,759
- Sure you wouldn't like another?
- Well...

72
00:06:47,927 --> 00:06:50,395
Well, maybe I will just
take one tiny nip more.

73
00:06:50,567 --> 00:06:53,365
Just to put the stopper on,
so to speak. Now, don't get worried.

74
00:06:53,527 --> 00:06:56,599
Your sister hasn't turned into a drunkard.
She's just all shaken up...

75
00:06:56,767 --> 00:07:00,077
...and hot and dirty and tired.

76
00:07:00,647 --> 00:07:02,126
Waiter.

77
00:07:02,447 --> 00:07:03,926
Waiter.

78
00:07:07,287 --> 00:07:10,040
- You want it hot?
- Scalding.

79
00:07:13,287 --> 00:07:15,676
- Stella.
- What is it, hon?

80
00:07:15,847 --> 00:07:18,884
There's only two rooms.
I don't see where you're gonna put me.

81
00:07:19,047 --> 00:07:20,719
We'll put you right here.

82
00:07:20,887 --> 00:07:24,562
What kind of a bed's this?
One of those collapsible beds?

83
00:07:24,727 --> 00:07:26,922
- Feel all right?
- Wonderful, honey.

84
00:07:27,087 --> 00:07:29,078
I don't like a bed that gives much.

85
00:07:29,687 --> 00:07:32,520
Stella, there's no door between
the two rooms, and Stanley...

86
00:07:32,687 --> 00:07:35,485
- Will it be decent?
- Oh, Stanley's Polish, you know.

87
00:07:35,647 --> 00:07:37,717
Oh, yeah.
Something like Irish, isn't it?

88
00:07:37,887 --> 00:07:39,286
Well...

89
00:07:39,447 --> 00:07:42,757
I bought some nice clothes
to meet all your lovely friends in.

90
00:07:43,167 --> 00:07:44,520
Well...

91
00:07:44,687 --> 00:07:46,484
I'm afraid
you won't think they're lovely.

92
00:07:46,647 --> 00:07:49,605
Well, anyway, I bought nice clothes
and I'll wear them.

93
00:07:50,407 --> 00:07:53,046
I guess you're hoping I'll say
I'll put up at a hotel.

94
00:07:53,207 --> 00:07:56,358
I'm not going to put up at a hotel.
I've got to be near you, Stella.

95
00:07:56,527 --> 00:07:59,758
I've got to be with people.
I can't be alone because...

96
00:08:00,127 --> 00:08:02,436
Because as you must have noticed, l...

97
00:08:02,607 --> 00:08:04,359
I'm not very well.

98
00:08:05,127 --> 00:08:07,163
You do seem a little...

99
00:08:07,727 --> 00:08:09,445
Will Stanley like me...

100
00:08:09,607 --> 00:08:12,724
...or will I just be a visiting in-law?
I couldn't stand that, Stella.

101
00:08:13,087 --> 00:08:16,557
You'll get along fine together.
If you just try not to compare him...

102
00:08:16,727 --> 00:08:18,877
- Oh, he was an officer?
- He was master sergeant...

103
00:08:19,047 --> 00:08:21,766
...in the Engineers Corps,
decorated four times.

104
00:08:21,927 --> 00:08:23,679
He had those on when you met him?

105
00:08:23,847 --> 00:08:26,441
I assure you I wasn't just blinded
by all the brass.

106
00:08:26,607 --> 00:08:28,518
- Oh, that's not what l...
- Of course, there...

107
00:08:28,687 --> 00:08:31,406
There were things
to adjust myself to later on.

108
00:08:31,807 --> 00:08:34,685
Such as his civilian background.

109
00:08:34,847 --> 00:08:36,803
How did he take it
when you said I was coming?

110
00:08:36,967 --> 00:08:39,765
- Oh, he's on the road a good deal.
- Oh, he travels?

111
00:08:40,247 --> 00:08:42,363
Good. I mean, isn't it?

112
00:08:42,527 --> 00:08:45,280
I can hardly stand it
when he's away for a night.

113
00:08:45,447 --> 00:08:46,641
Oh, Stella.

114
00:08:46,807 --> 00:08:49,037
When he's away for a week,
I nearly go wild.

115
00:08:49,207 --> 00:08:51,357
- Gracious.
- When he comes back...

116
00:08:51,527 --> 00:08:54,360
...I cry in his lap like a baby.

117
00:08:55,447 --> 00:08:57,881
I guess that's what's meant
by being in love.

118
00:09:01,567 --> 00:09:03,125
Stella.

119
00:09:05,327 --> 00:09:08,763
I haven't asked you the things you
probably thought I was going to ask...

120
00:09:08,927 --> 00:09:13,443
...so I'll expect you to be understanding
about what I have to tell you.

121
00:09:13,607 --> 00:09:14,835
What, Blanche?

122
00:09:15,007 --> 00:09:19,364
You'll reproach me. I know you're bound
to reproach me, but before you do...

123
00:09:19,527 --> 00:09:22,644
...take into consideration you left.
I stayed and struggled.

124
00:09:22,807 --> 00:09:25,082
You came to New Orleans
and looked out for yourself.

125
00:09:25,247 --> 00:09:27,602
I stayed at Belle Reve
and tried to hold it together.

126
00:09:27,767 --> 00:09:30,122
Oh, I'm not meaning this
in any reproachful way.

127
00:09:30,287 --> 00:09:34,246
- But the burden fell on my shoulders.
- Best I could do was make my own living.

128
00:09:34,407 --> 00:09:36,716
But you were the one
that abandoned Belle Reve, not I.

129
00:09:36,887 --> 00:09:38,957
I fought for it,
bled for it, almost died for it.

130
00:09:39,127 --> 00:09:40,879
Stop this outburst.
Tell me what happened.

131
00:09:41,047 --> 00:09:44,881
- I knew you'd take this attitude about it.
- About what? Please!

132
00:09:46,047 --> 00:09:47,639
The loss.

133
00:09:49,287 --> 00:09:50,720
The loss.

134
00:09:51,087 --> 00:09:53,999
Belle Reve? Lost, is it?

135
00:09:56,407 --> 00:09:57,681
Yes, Stella.

136
00:09:58,687 --> 00:10:01,042
But how did it go? What happened?

137
00:10:01,727 --> 00:10:04,321
- You're a fine one to ask me how it went.
- Blanche.

138
00:10:04,487 --> 00:10:06,762
You're a fine one to stand there
accusing me of it.

139
00:10:06,927 --> 00:10:09,395
- I won't stay in this house.
- Blanche!

140
00:10:14,727 --> 00:10:17,241
- Blanche.
- I, I, I took the blows...

141
00:10:17,407 --> 00:10:19,238
...on my face and my body.

142
00:10:19,407 --> 00:10:23,480
All of those deaths,
the long parade to the graveyard.

143
00:10:23,647 --> 00:10:27,560
Father, Mother,
Margaret, that dreadful way...

144
00:10:27,727 --> 00:10:30,161
You just came home
in time for funerals, Stella.

145
00:10:30,327 --> 00:10:32,887
And funerals are pretty
compared to deaths.

146
00:10:33,047 --> 00:10:36,323
How do you think all that sickness
and dying was paid for?

147
00:10:36,487 --> 00:10:38,557
Death is expensive, Miss Stella.

148
00:10:38,727 --> 00:10:42,163
And I, with my pitiful salary
at the school...

149
00:10:42,647 --> 00:10:44,000
Yes, accuse me.

150
00:10:44,167 --> 00:10:47,079
Stand there and stare at me,
thinking I let the place go.

151
00:10:47,247 --> 00:10:49,522
I let the place go? Where were you?

152
00:10:49,687 --> 00:10:52,804
- In there with your Polack.
- Blanche, be still. That's enough.

153
00:10:52,967 --> 00:10:56,482
- Stella. Stella, you're crying?
- Does that surprise you?

154
00:10:58,207 --> 00:11:00,163
Mitch, we gonna play
at your house tomorrow?

155
00:11:00,327 --> 00:11:02,283
No, not at my house.
My mother's still sick.

156
00:11:02,447 --> 00:11:04,961
- All right, you bring the beer.
- Break it up down there.

157
00:11:05,127 --> 00:11:08,403
- I made that spaghetti and ate it myself.
- Now, honey, I told you...

158
00:11:08,567 --> 00:11:10,956
...and told you
we were playing Jack's beer.

159
00:11:12,367 --> 00:11:14,642
What's so funny?
You never phoned me once.

160
00:11:14,807 --> 00:11:16,763
I told you at breakfast.
I phoned you at lunch.

161
00:11:16,927 --> 00:11:18,519
Why don't you get yourself in here!

162
00:11:18,687 --> 00:11:21,997
- Do you want it in the newspapers?
- I'm sick and tired of chasing you.

163
00:11:38,007 --> 00:11:39,918
You must be Stanley.

164
00:11:40,087 --> 00:11:41,645
I'm Blanche.

165
00:11:42,087 --> 00:11:43,805
Oh, you're Stella's sister.

166
00:11:44,167 --> 00:11:45,486
Yes.

167
00:11:46,007 --> 00:11:47,486
Oh, hiya.

168
00:11:47,647 --> 00:11:49,319
Yeah, where's the little woman?

169
00:11:50,487 --> 00:11:52,239
In the bathroom.

170
00:11:55,247 --> 00:11:57,841
- Well, where you from, Blanche?
- Why, I...

171
00:11:58,007 --> 00:11:59,326
I live in Auriol.

172
00:11:59,767 --> 00:12:01,883
In Auriol. Auriol, huh?

173
00:12:02,087 --> 00:12:05,477
Oh, yeah, that's right. Auriol.
That's not my territory.

174
00:12:06,007 --> 00:12:08,726
Man, liquor goes fast
in the hot weather.

175
00:12:09,047 --> 00:12:12,119
- You want a shot?
- No, I rarely touch it.

176
00:12:12,927 --> 00:12:17,205
Well, there's some people that rarely
touch it, but it touches them often.

177
00:12:21,287 --> 00:12:23,755
Mind if I make myself comfortable?
My shirt is sticking...

178
00:12:23,927 --> 00:12:25,645
Please. Please do.

179
00:12:25,807 --> 00:12:28,082
"Be comfortable." That's my motto,
where I come from.

180
00:12:28,247 --> 00:12:31,796
It's mine too. It's hard to stay
looking fresh in hot weather.

181
00:12:31,967 --> 00:12:34,117
Why, I haven't washed
or even powdered...

182
00:12:34,287 --> 00:12:36,084
...and here you are.

183
00:12:36,647 --> 00:12:40,356
You gotta be careful. You sitting around
in a damp thing, you catch a cold.

184
00:12:40,527 --> 00:12:43,599
Especially when you been
exercising hard, like bowling is.

185
00:12:44,887 --> 00:12:48,084
- Well, you're the teacher, aren't you?
- Yes.

186
00:12:48,247 --> 00:12:51,444
- What do you teach?
- English.

187
00:12:51,647 --> 00:12:53,956
Well, I never was a very good
English student.

188
00:12:55,607 --> 00:12:58,679
- How long you here for?
- Why, I don't know yet.

189
00:12:58,967 --> 00:13:00,286
You gonna shack up here?

190
00:13:01,127 --> 00:13:04,085
I thought I would,
if it's not inconvenient for you all.

191
00:13:04,887 --> 00:13:06,240
Good.

192
00:13:09,407 --> 00:13:11,159
Traveling wears me out.

193
00:13:11,927 --> 00:13:14,680
- Well, take it easy.
- What was that?

194
00:13:16,887 --> 00:13:18,718
Oh, those cats.

195
00:13:23,287 --> 00:13:27,678
Hey, Stella.
What did you do, fall asleep in there?

196
00:13:31,287 --> 00:13:34,518
Well, I guess I'm gonna strike you
as being the unrefined type, huh?

197
00:13:36,407 --> 00:13:39,922
You know,
Stella spoke a good deal about you.

198
00:13:41,167 --> 00:13:43,078
She said you were married once,
weren't you?

199
00:13:48,167 --> 00:13:49,520
Yes.

200
00:13:50,327 --> 00:13:52,204
When I was quite young.

201
00:13:52,367 --> 00:13:53,766
Yeah? What happened?

202
00:13:53,927 --> 00:13:56,395
- <i>Yeah? What happened?</i>
- The boy...

203
00:13:57,167 --> 00:13:58,919
The boy died.

204
00:14:14,607 --> 00:14:16,245
I'm afraid l...

205
00:14:17,447 --> 00:14:19,278
I'm going to be sick.

206
00:14:20,887 --> 00:14:26,280
Fresh fish! Fresh fish! Fresh fish!

207
00:14:36,727 --> 00:14:38,957
- Looks like she's fixing to stay a while.
- Yeah.

208
00:14:39,127 --> 00:14:40,879
- Hey, Stan, are we playing tonight?
- Yeah.

209
00:14:41,047 --> 00:14:42,321
Well, I figured maybe we...

210
00:14:42,487 --> 00:14:44,557
- Forget about maybe. It's the same.
- Stanley!

211
00:14:44,727 --> 00:14:46,080
- Oh, hi, Steve.
- Put it down.

212
00:14:46,247 --> 00:14:48,238
- Now I'll go get the other one?
- Yes.

213
00:14:48,407 --> 00:14:50,363
- Thanks, darling.
- Stella?

214
00:14:50,527 --> 00:14:52,882
- Yes?
- Is that Stanley back with my trunk?

215
00:14:53,047 --> 00:14:54,685
- Yes, Blanche.
- Honey...

216
00:14:54,847 --> 00:14:58,317
...will you get my blue net out for me?
- All right, Blanche.

217
00:14:58,487 --> 00:15:00,762
It was so good of Stanley
to call for my trunk.

218
00:15:00,927 --> 00:15:03,122
He was glad to do it.

219
00:15:03,287 --> 00:15:05,676
- I'll see you later.
- All right. Listen, don't forget.

220
00:15:05,847 --> 00:15:08,520
Honey, I'm taking Blanche
to Galatoire's for supper tonight...

221
00:15:08,687 --> 00:15:10,996
...and then to a show
because it's your poker night.

222
00:15:11,167 --> 00:15:13,840
How about my supper?
I'm not going to Galatoire's tonight.

223
00:15:14,007 --> 00:15:15,918
I put you a cold plate on ice.

224
00:15:16,087 --> 00:15:18,965
I'm gonna try to keep Blanche
out until the party breaks up.

225
00:15:19,127 --> 00:15:22,039
- I don't know how she'll take it.
- Isn't that just dandy?

226
00:15:22,207 --> 00:15:24,084
So you'd better give me some money.

227
00:15:24,247 --> 00:15:25,441
Hey, where is she now?

228
00:15:25,607 --> 00:15:28,565
She's soaking in a hot tub
to quiet her nerves.

229
00:15:28,727 --> 00:15:30,285
She's terribly upset.

230
00:15:30,447 --> 00:15:31,766
Over what?

231
00:15:31,927 --> 00:15:35,158
She's been through such an ordeal.
We lost Belle Reve.

232
00:15:35,607 --> 00:15:37,996
What, the place in the country?

233
00:15:38,167 --> 00:15:40,727
- Well, how?
- It had to be sacrificed or something.

234
00:15:40,887 --> 00:15:44,482
Honey, look. When she comes in, say
something nice about her appearance.

235
00:15:44,647 --> 00:15:47,241
And, oh, don't mention the baby.

236
00:15:47,407 --> 00:15:51,002
I haven't said anything yet. I'm waiting
until she gets in a quieter condition.

237
00:15:51,167 --> 00:15:54,477
- Try to understand her and be nice to her.
- All right.

238
00:15:54,647 --> 00:15:56,683
She wasn't expecting
to find us in such a place.

239
00:15:56,847 --> 00:15:59,077
- All right.
- I tried to gloss things over a little...

240
00:15:59,247 --> 00:16:00,316
...in my letters.

241
00:16:00,487 --> 00:16:03,479
Admire her dress.
Tell her she's looking wonderful.

242
00:16:03,647 --> 00:16:06,286
It's important to Blanche.
Her little weakness.

243
00:16:06,447 --> 00:16:08,915
Okay, honey, I get the idea, but...

244
00:16:09,087 --> 00:16:12,477
Now, let's just skip back a little, the way
you said the place was disposed of.

245
00:16:12,647 --> 00:16:13,841
Oh, yeah.

246
00:16:14,007 --> 00:16:16,601
Well, how about
a few more details on that subject?

247
00:16:16,767 --> 00:16:20,601
Honey, look, it's best not to talk much
about it until she's calmed down.

248
00:16:20,767 --> 00:16:24,806
Is that gonna be the deal? Sister Blanche
can't be annoyed with details right now?

249
00:16:24,967 --> 00:16:27,037
Well, you saw how she was last night.

250
00:16:27,207 --> 00:16:30,438
I saw how she was. Now, let's
cop a gander at the bill of sale.

251
00:16:30,607 --> 00:16:32,484
I haven't seen any.

252
00:16:32,647 --> 00:16:36,003
What do you mean? She didn't show you
papers, deed of sale, nothing like that?

253
00:16:36,167 --> 00:16:37,998
Seemed like it wasn't sold.

254
00:16:38,167 --> 00:16:40,522
Well, now, what was it, then?
Giveaway to charity?

255
00:16:40,687 --> 00:16:42,803
- She'll hear you.
- I don't care if she hears me.

256
00:16:42,967 --> 00:16:45,720
- Now, let's see the papers.
- Honey, there weren't any papers.

257
00:16:45,887 --> 00:16:49,004
She didn't show any papers.
I don't care about papers.

258
00:16:49,167 --> 00:16:52,477
Wait. Now, listen, did you ever hear
of the Napoleonic Code, Stella?

259
00:16:52,647 --> 00:16:55,798
- I haven't heard of the Napoleonic Code.
- All right. Okay, then.

260
00:16:55,967 --> 00:16:58,720
- Let me enlighten you on a point or two.
- Yes?

261
00:16:58,887 --> 00:17:02,482
We got here in the state of Louisiana
what's known as the Napoleonic Code.

262
00:17:02,647 --> 00:17:05,844
According to which, what belongs to
the wife belongs to the husband also...

263
00:17:06,007 --> 00:17:07,360
...and vice versa.

264
00:17:07,527 --> 00:17:09,040
Will you listen.

265
00:17:09,207 --> 00:17:11,323
Take, for instance, I had
that piece of property...

266
00:17:11,487 --> 00:17:13,842
My head is swimming.

267
00:17:14,887 --> 00:17:17,276
Oh, well, all right, dear.

268
00:17:17,447 --> 00:17:18,721
Okay.

269
00:17:19,207 --> 00:17:21,596
We'll wait till she's through
soaking in the hot tub...

270
00:17:21,767 --> 00:17:25,237
...then I'm gonna inquire if she's
acquainted with the Napoleonic Code.

271
00:17:25,567 --> 00:17:27,364
Oh, Stanley, don't be so silly.

272
00:17:27,527 --> 00:17:30,405
It looks to me like you been swindled.
And when you get swindled...

273
00:17:30,567 --> 00:17:33,798
...under Napoleonic Code, I get swindled
too. I don't like to get swindled.

274
00:17:33,967 --> 00:17:35,161
Oh, Stanley...

275
00:17:35,327 --> 00:17:37,841
...you've no idea how ridiculous
you're being...

276
00:17:38,007 --> 00:17:39,645
...when you suggest that my sister...

277
00:17:39,807 --> 00:17:43,436
...or I or anyone else of our family could
have perpetrated a swindle on anyone.

278
00:17:43,607 --> 00:17:46,724
Oh, come on, now. Where's the money
if the place was sold?

279
00:17:46,887 --> 00:17:48,878
Not sold. Lost!

280
00:17:49,047 --> 00:17:50,275
- Lost.
- Come here.

281
00:17:50,447 --> 00:17:53,837
- Stanley.
- Will you open your eyes to this stuff?

282
00:17:54,007 --> 00:17:56,726
- What, she got this out of teacher's pay?
- Oh, hush.

283
00:17:56,887 --> 00:18:00,562
Look at these fine feathers and furs
that she comes to preen herself in here?

284
00:18:00,727 --> 00:18:03,560
What is this article?
That's a solid-gold dress, I believe.

285
00:18:03,727 --> 00:18:06,958
- Oh, honest.
- This one here. What is that, a fox piece?

286
00:18:07,127 --> 00:18:09,595
- Stanley!
- A genuine fur fox a half a mile long.

287
00:18:09,767 --> 00:18:11,883
Where are your fox pieces?

288
00:18:12,047 --> 00:18:15,323
This is bushy snow-white ones, no less.
Where are your white fox furs?

289
00:18:15,487 --> 00:18:19,116
Those are inexpensive summer furs
that Blanche has had a long time.

290
00:18:19,287 --> 00:18:22,085
I have an acquaintance who deals
in this sort of merchandise.

291
00:18:22,247 --> 00:18:25,523
- He's coming to make an appraisal.
- Don't be such an idiot, Stanley.

292
00:18:25,687 --> 00:18:29,600
Listen, I'm gonna bet you there's
a thousand dollars invested in this stuff.

293
00:18:29,767 --> 00:18:32,565
Well, now, what is that?
That's the treasure chest of a pirate?

294
00:18:32,727 --> 00:18:35,844
- Oh, Stanley. Would you...?
- That's pearls, Stella. Ropes of them.

295
00:18:36,287 --> 00:18:38,596
What is this sister of yours,
a deep-sea diver?

296
00:18:38,767 --> 00:18:41,679
Bracelets, solid gold. Where are
your pearls and gold bracelets?

297
00:18:41,847 --> 00:18:43,166
Be still, Stanley.

298
00:18:43,327 --> 00:18:45,318
And here. Diamonds.
A crown for an empress.

299
00:18:45,487 --> 00:18:48,923
A rhinestone tiara
she wore to a costume ball.

300
00:18:49,087 --> 00:18:51,601
- What is rhinestone?
- Next door to glass.

301
00:18:51,767 --> 00:18:52,995
Yeah.

302
00:18:53,167 --> 00:18:56,125
I have an acquaintance who works in
a jewelry store and he's coming...

303
00:18:56,287 --> 00:18:57,959
...to make an appraisal of that stuff.

304
00:18:58,127 --> 00:19:03,076
- Here's your plantation fella, right here.
- You know l... Stupid and horrid.

305
00:19:03,247 --> 00:19:06,284
You stay away from these things
before she comes out of the bathroom.

306
00:19:06,447 --> 00:19:09,166
The Kowalskis and the DuBois
got a different notion on this.

307
00:19:09,327 --> 00:19:12,876
Indeed they have, thank heavens.
I'm going outside.

308
00:19:13,767 --> 00:19:15,200
Go ahead.

309
00:19:17,687 --> 00:19:20,485
You come on out with me
while Blanche is getting dressed.

310
00:19:20,647 --> 00:19:23,161
Now, since when
are you giving me orders?

311
00:19:23,327 --> 00:19:26,319
Are you gonna stay here
and insult her?

312
00:19:26,487 --> 00:19:28,717
You bet your life I'm gonna stay here.

313
00:19:44,447 --> 00:19:45,675
Hello, Stanley.

314
00:19:47,327 --> 00:19:51,559
Here I am, all freshly bathed and scented
and feeling like a brand-new human being.

315
00:19:51,727 --> 00:19:53,080
Oh, that's good.

316
00:19:53,687 --> 00:19:58,283
Will you excuse me
while I put on my pretty new dress?

317
00:19:58,447 --> 00:20:00,039
Go ahead.

318
00:20:18,727 --> 00:20:20,319
Thank you.

319
00:20:33,607 --> 00:20:36,519
I understand there's to be
a little card party here tonight...

320
00:20:36,687 --> 00:20:39,804
...to which we ladies
are cordially not invited.

321
00:20:39,967 --> 00:20:41,195
That's right.

322
00:20:41,367 --> 00:20:43,961
Where...? Where is Stella?

323
00:20:44,887 --> 00:20:47,117
She's out there on the porch.

324
00:20:53,607 --> 00:20:55,916
I'm going to ask a favor of you
in a moment.

325
00:20:57,287 --> 00:20:59,596
Well, now, what's that gonna be,
I wonder.

326
00:20:59,927 --> 00:21:01,918
Some buttons in back.

327
00:21:02,807 --> 00:21:04,559
You may enter.

328
00:21:08,047 --> 00:21:09,366
How do I look?

329
00:21:09,527 --> 00:21:11,040
You look okay.

330
00:21:11,207 --> 00:21:13,437
Well, thanks. Now the button.

331
00:21:18,647 --> 00:21:20,603
Well, I can't do no more with them.

332
00:21:20,767 --> 00:21:22,678
You men with your big, clumsy fingers.

333
00:21:22,847 --> 00:21:25,725
- May I have a drag on your cig?
- Yeah, have one for yourself.

334
00:21:25,887 --> 00:21:27,684
Why, thank you. It...

335
00:21:27,847 --> 00:21:30,361
It looks like my trunk has exploded.

336
00:21:30,527 --> 00:21:32,916
Me and Stella was helping you unpack.

337
00:21:33,647 --> 00:21:36,115
You certainly did a fast
and thorough job of it.

338
00:21:36,287 --> 00:21:39,518
Well, certainly looks like you raided
some stylish shops in Paris, Blanche.

339
00:21:39,687 --> 00:21:41,359
Clothes are my passion.

340
00:21:41,527 --> 00:21:43,757
How much does it cost
for a string of furs like that?

341
00:21:43,927 --> 00:21:45,997
Why, these were a tribute
from an admirer of mine.

342
00:21:46,167 --> 00:21:47,885
He must have had a lot of admiration.

343
00:21:48,047 --> 00:21:50,766
In my youth I excited some admiration,
but look at me now.

344
00:21:50,927 --> 00:21:54,636
Would you think it possible that I
was once considered to be attractive?

345
00:21:55,887 --> 00:21:57,240
Your looks are okay.

346
00:21:57,687 --> 00:22:00,281
- I was fishing for a compliment.
- I don't go for that stuff.

347
00:22:00,527 --> 00:22:02,563
- What stuff?
- Compliments to women about looks.

348
00:22:02,727 --> 00:22:06,436
I never met a dame didn't know she was
good-looking or not without being told.

349
00:22:06,607 --> 00:22:09,599
And some of them give themselves
credit for more than they've got.

350
00:22:09,767 --> 00:22:12,725
I once went out with a dame
who told me, "I'm the glamorous type."

351
00:22:13,047 --> 00:22:15,925
She says, "I am the glamorous type."
I says, "So what?"

352
00:22:16,087 --> 00:22:18,760
- And what did she say then?
- She didn't say nothing.

353
00:22:18,927 --> 00:22:21,725
- That shut her up like a clam.
- Did it end the romance?

354
00:22:21,887 --> 00:22:24,685
Well, it ended the conversation,
that was all.

355
00:22:24,847 --> 00:22:27,759
There's some men that are took in
by this Hollywood glamour stuff...

356
00:22:27,927 --> 00:22:31,283
...and there's some men that aren't.
- You belong in the second category.

357
00:22:31,447 --> 00:22:33,836
- That's right.
- I can't imagine any witch of a woman...

358
00:22:34,007 --> 00:22:35,918
...casting a spell over you.
- That's right.

359
00:22:36,087 --> 00:22:38,317
You're simple,
straightforward and honest.

360
00:22:38,487 --> 00:22:41,365
A little bit on the primitive side,
I should think.

361
00:22:41,527 --> 00:22:44,724
- To interest you a woman would have to...
- To lay her cards on the table.

362
00:22:44,887 --> 00:22:47,447
Well, I never did care
for wishy-washy people.

363
00:22:47,607 --> 00:22:50,326
That was why when you walked
in last night, I said to myself:

364
00:22:50,487 --> 00:22:52,603
"My sister has married a man."
Of course.

365
00:22:52,767 --> 00:22:55,361
- That was all I could tell...
- How about cutting the rebop!

366
00:22:55,527 --> 00:22:56,676
Stanley!

367
00:22:58,327 --> 00:23:00,716
Come on outside with me
and let Blanche finish dressing.

368
00:23:00,887 --> 00:23:02,718
- I'm finished dressing.
- Then come on out.

369
00:23:02,887 --> 00:23:04,878
- Your sister and I are having a talk.
- Honey...

370
00:23:05,047 --> 00:23:07,880
...run to the drugstore and get me
a lemon Coke with chipped ice.

371
00:23:08,047 --> 00:23:10,720
Will you do that for me,
sweetie, please? Please.

372
00:23:12,287 --> 00:23:13,845
All right.

373
00:23:18,807 --> 00:23:20,638
Poor thing was out there listening to us.

374
00:23:20,807 --> 00:23:24,243
And I have an idea she doesn't
understand you as well as I do.

375
00:23:25,847 --> 00:23:29,157
All right now, Mr. Kowalski, let us
proceed without any more digression.

376
00:23:29,327 --> 00:23:32,956
I'm ready to answer all questions.
I have nothing to hide.

377
00:23:33,127 --> 00:23:34,640
What is it?

378
00:23:35,767 --> 00:23:40,477
In the state of Louisiana we got here
what's known as the Napoleonic Code.

379
00:23:40,647 --> 00:23:44,686
Which says, what belongs to the wife
belongs to the husband and vice versa.

380
00:23:44,847 --> 00:23:47,077
My, but you have
an impressive judicial air.

381
00:23:47,247 --> 00:23:50,956
If I didn't know that you was my wife's
sister, I would get ideas about you.

382
00:23:52,767 --> 00:23:56,726
- Such as what?
- Don't play so dumb. You know what.

383
00:23:57,967 --> 00:24:00,561
All right. Cards on the table.

384
00:24:00,727 --> 00:24:06,120
I know I fib a good deal. After all,
a woman's charm is 50 percent illusion.

385
00:24:06,927 --> 00:24:09,725
But when a thing is important
I tell the truth.

386
00:24:09,887 --> 00:24:11,320
And this is the truth:

387
00:24:11,487 --> 00:24:16,561
I never cheated my sister, or you, or
anyone else on earth as long as I lived.

388
00:24:16,727 --> 00:24:20,879
- Where are the papers, in your trunk?
- Everything I own is in that trunk.

389
00:24:23,567 --> 00:24:27,242
What are you thinking of? What's in the
back of that little boy's mind of yours?

390
00:24:27,407 --> 00:24:29,363
Let me do that.
It'll be faster and simple.

391
00:24:29,527 --> 00:24:34,078
- I keep my papers mostly in this tin box.
- What are those underneath?

392
00:24:36,047 --> 00:24:37,958
Those are love letters...

393
00:24:38,127 --> 00:24:40,277
...yellowing with antiquity...

394
00:24:40,447 --> 00:24:43,519
...all from one boy. Give those back.
- I'm just gonna have a look.

395
00:24:43,687 --> 00:24:46,645
- The touch of your hands insults them.
- Now, don't pull that stuff.

396
00:24:46,807 --> 00:24:50,402
Now that you've touched them,
I'll burn them.

397
00:24:51,007 --> 00:24:52,725
What are they?

398
00:24:53,927 --> 00:24:56,964
Poems the dead boy wrote.

399
00:24:57,127 --> 00:25:00,881
I hurt him the way that you would
like to hurt me. But you can't.

400
00:25:01,047 --> 00:25:05,916
I'm not young and vulnerable anymore,
but my young husband was, and I...

401
00:25:07,087 --> 00:25:08,839
Never mind about that.

402
00:25:09,887 --> 00:25:11,445
Just give them back to me.

403
00:25:14,727 --> 00:25:16,399
Thank you.

404
00:25:17,047 --> 00:25:19,766
What'd you mean by saying
you have to burn them up?

405
00:25:20,087 --> 00:25:21,884
I'm sorry.

406
00:25:22,647 --> 00:25:25,036
I must have lost my head for a moment.

407
00:25:25,207 --> 00:25:29,280
Everyone has something they won't
let others touch because of their...

408
00:25:29,527 --> 00:25:31,677
Their intimate nature.

409
00:25:38,167 --> 00:25:39,919
Ambler and Ambler.

410
00:25:40,087 --> 00:25:41,839
Crabtree.

411
00:25:42,647 --> 00:25:45,036
- More Ambler and Ambler.
- What's Ambler and Ambler?

412
00:25:45,207 --> 00:25:46,765
A firm that made loans on the place.

413
00:25:46,927 --> 00:25:49,600
- It was lost on a mortgage.
- That must have been what happened.

414
00:25:49,767 --> 00:25:52,406
I don't want if, ands or buts.
What's the rest of the papers?

415
00:25:52,567 --> 00:25:55,923
There are thousands of papers
stretching back over hundreds of years...

416
00:25:56,087 --> 00:25:57,315
...affecting Belle Reve...

417
00:25:57,487 --> 00:26:00,160
...as piece by piece,
our improvident grandfathers...

418
00:26:00,327 --> 00:26:02,636
...exchanged the land
for their epic debauches...

419
00:26:02,807 --> 00:26:04,206
...to put it mildly.

420
00:26:04,367 --> 00:26:07,279
Until finally, all that was left...
And Stella can verify that.

421
00:26:07,447 --> 00:26:08,721
- was the house itself.

422
00:26:08,887 --> 00:26:12,323
And about 20 acres of ground,
including a graveyard...

423
00:26:12,487 --> 00:26:16,275
...to which now all but Stella
and I have retreated.

424
00:26:16,447 --> 00:26:19,644
Here they are, all of them.
All papers.

425
00:26:19,807 --> 00:26:23,925
I endow you with them. Take them,
peruse them, commit them to memory.

426
00:26:24,087 --> 00:26:26,317
I think it's wonderfully fitting
that Belle Reve...

427
00:26:26,487 --> 00:26:30,162
...should finally be this bunch of old
papers in your big, capable hands.

428
00:26:33,207 --> 00:26:36,040
I wonder if Stella's come back
with my lemon Coke.

429
00:26:37,047 --> 00:26:39,925
I got a lawyer acquaintance,
we'll study this out.

430
00:26:40,567 --> 00:26:43,798
Present them to him
with a box of aspirin tablets.

431
00:26:45,407 --> 00:26:50,640
Under the Napoleonic Code a man has got
to take an interest in his wife's affairs.

432
00:26:50,807 --> 00:26:53,196
And I mean especially now
that she's gonna have a baby.

433
00:26:56,567 --> 00:26:58,000
Stella?

434
00:26:59,087 --> 00:27:01,282
Stella, going to have a baby?

435
00:27:05,367 --> 00:27:08,518
I didn't know
she was going to have a baby.

436
00:27:13,367 --> 00:27:15,164
Stella.

437
00:27:15,767 --> 00:27:21,205
Oh, Stella for star,
how lovely to have a baby.

438
00:27:22,127 --> 00:27:23,719
Honey, everything's all right.

439
00:27:23,887 --> 00:27:25,286
We thrashed it out.

440
00:27:25,447 --> 00:27:27,642
I feel a bit shaky,
but I think I handled it nicely.

441
00:27:27,807 --> 00:27:29,763
I laughed and treated it all as a joke.

442
00:27:29,927 --> 00:27:32,487
I laughed and called him a little boy
and flirted. Here.

443
00:27:32,647 --> 00:27:34,797
I was flirting with your husband, Stella.

444
00:27:34,967 --> 00:27:37,037
The guests are gathering
for the poker party.

445
00:27:40,407 --> 00:27:42,796
- Hi, Stella.
- Hi, Steve.

446
00:27:45,207 --> 00:27:46,640
I'm sorry he did that to you.

447
00:27:46,807 --> 00:27:51,642
Why, I guess he's just not the type
that goes for jasmine perfume.

448
00:27:51,807 --> 00:27:55,482
Maybe he's what we need to mix with
our blood now we've lost Belle Reve...

449
00:27:55,647 --> 00:27:59,242
...and have to go on
without Belle Reve to protect us.

450
00:28:00,287 --> 00:28:03,677
Oh, how pretty the sky is.

451
00:28:03,847 --> 00:28:05,644
I ought to go there on a rocket...

452
00:28:05,807 --> 00:28:07,399
...that never comes down.

453
00:28:07,567 --> 00:28:09,603
Which way do we go now, Stella?

454
00:28:09,767 --> 00:28:11,166
This way?

455
00:28:11,327 --> 00:28:13,283
No, hon, this way.

456
00:28:13,447 --> 00:28:16,405
The blind are leading the blind.

457
00:28:16,567 --> 00:28:18,717
Red hots!

458
00:28:36,847 --> 00:28:39,042
Are you going upstairs
and tell her to cut that out?

459
00:28:39,207 --> 00:28:41,562
If I go up, I won't come down.
Let's just forget it.

460
00:28:42,607 --> 00:28:46,122
Remember that night she poured boiling
water through them cracks in the floor?

461
00:28:57,687 --> 00:28:58,961
I gotta go home pretty soon.

462
00:28:59,127 --> 00:29:00,924
- Come on, what do you say?
- No, I'm out.

463
00:29:01,087 --> 00:29:03,555
Every time you win a big pot,
you're out like stout.

464
00:29:03,727 --> 00:29:05,763
I got a sick mother
and she don't go to sleep...

465
00:29:05,927 --> 00:29:07,758
...until I get in.
- What do you say?

466
00:29:07,927 --> 00:29:09,360
I'm gonna wash up.

467
00:29:11,767 --> 00:29:14,440
- Stella?
- Yes, Eunice?

468
00:29:14,607 --> 00:29:17,644
You tell them guys
the kettle's on the stove.

469
00:29:17,807 --> 00:29:19,923
I'm gonna break up the game.

470
00:29:20,127 --> 00:29:23,802
- What did she mean by that?
- She'll pour it straight through the cracks.

471
00:29:24,007 --> 00:29:26,441
Stella, wait. Wait till I powder.

472
00:29:26,607 --> 00:29:28,086
I feel so hot and frazzled.

473
00:29:28,247 --> 00:29:30,636
- Do I look done in?
- You look as fresh as a daisy.

474
00:29:31,247 --> 00:29:33,317
One that's been picked a few days.

475
00:29:34,167 --> 00:29:37,682
Why don't someone go to the Chinaman's
and bring back a load of chop suey?

476
00:29:37,847 --> 00:29:41,362
- I'm losing and you want to eat.
- Well, I see you boys are still at it.

477
00:29:41,527 --> 00:29:43,518
- Where you been?
- Blanche and I took in a show.

478
00:29:43,687 --> 00:29:46,201
Blanche, honey, this is Mr. Gonzalez
and Mr. Hubbell.

479
00:29:46,367 --> 00:29:48,278
How do you do?
Please don't get up.

480
00:29:48,447 --> 00:29:50,517
Nobody's getting up here,
so don't get worried.

481
00:29:50,687 --> 00:29:53,997
- Poker is so fascinating. Could I kibitz?
- You could not.

482
00:29:54,247 --> 00:29:56,238
Why don't you women
go on up to Eunice's?

483
00:29:56,407 --> 00:29:59,444
- How long's this game going to continue?
- Till we get ready to quit.

484
00:29:59,607 --> 00:30:01,518
You should call it quits
after one more hand.

485
00:30:01,687 --> 00:30:04,406
- Go up to Eunice's.
- Hey, that's my coat.

486
00:30:05,687 --> 00:30:08,440
That's not fun, Stanley.

487
00:30:09,887 --> 00:30:13,163
It makes me so mad
when he does that in front of people.

488
00:30:13,327 --> 00:30:15,443
- I think I'll go bathe.
- Again?

489
00:30:15,607 --> 00:30:17,837
My nerves are in knots.
Is the bathroom occupied?

490
00:30:18,007 --> 00:30:19,281
I don't know.

491
00:30:19,447 --> 00:30:21,642
- Oh, good evening.
- Oh, hello.

492
00:30:22,847 --> 00:30:24,644
Blanche, this is Harold Mitchell.

493
00:30:24,807 --> 00:30:27,002
- This is my sister, Blanche DuBois.
- How do you do.

494
00:30:27,167 --> 00:30:29,965
- How do you do, Miss DuBois.
- How's your mother now, Mitch?

495
00:30:30,127 --> 00:30:31,606
Oh, she's about the same, thanks.

496
00:30:31,767 --> 00:30:34,327
She appreciated your
sending over that custard.

497
00:30:35,287 --> 00:30:37,084
Oh, excuse me, please.

498
00:30:37,887 --> 00:30:39,525
Excuse me.

499
00:30:49,207 --> 00:30:52,563
- That one seems superior to the others.
- Does he?

500
00:30:52,727 --> 00:30:56,436
- I thought he had a sort of sensitive look.
- His mother's sick.

501
00:30:56,607 --> 00:30:59,041
- Is he married?
- No.

502
00:30:59,247 --> 00:31:02,478
- Is he a wolf?
- Why, Blanche.

503
00:31:02,647 --> 00:31:05,684
- Well, no, I don't think he would be.
- What does he do?

504
00:31:05,847 --> 00:31:09,044
He's on the Precision Bench
in the Spare Parts Department.

505
00:31:09,207 --> 00:31:11,163
The plant that Stanley travels for.

506
00:31:11,327 --> 00:31:13,363
- Is that something much?
- No.

507
00:31:13,527 --> 00:31:16,325
Stanley's the only one in his crowd
likely to get any work.

508
00:31:20,127 --> 00:31:22,687
Hey, Blanche,
you're standing in the light.

509
00:31:23,767 --> 00:31:25,519
Am I? Gracious.

510
00:31:27,127 --> 00:31:28,640
You ought to see their wives.

511
00:31:28,807 --> 00:31:31,275
Oh, I can imagine.
Big, beefy things, I suppose.

512
00:31:31,447 --> 00:31:33,483
- Do you know that one upstairs?
- Oh, yes.

513
00:31:33,647 --> 00:31:36,241
Well, one night...

514
00:31:37,047 --> 00:31:38,480
And the plaster...!

515
00:31:38,687 --> 00:31:40,006
Hey, you hens!

516
00:31:40,167 --> 00:31:43,045
- Cut out that cackling in there.
- You can't hear us.

517
00:31:43,207 --> 00:31:46,358
Well, you can hear me,
and I told you to hush up.

518
00:31:47,087 --> 00:31:48,281
Stella.

519
00:31:48,447 --> 00:31:51,917
Look, this is my house
and I'll talk as much as I want to.

520
00:31:52,767 --> 00:31:55,964
- Stella, don't start a row.
- Oh, he's half-drunk.

521
00:31:56,287 --> 00:31:58,084
I'll be out in a minute.

522
00:32:22,327 --> 00:32:24,079
What do you say, Mitch?

523
00:32:25,527 --> 00:32:26,801
Come on, Mitch, are you in?

524
00:32:27,927 --> 00:32:29,246
No, I'm out.

525
00:32:29,407 --> 00:32:30,999
Who turned that on in there?

526
00:32:32,207 --> 00:32:34,641
- I did. Do you mind?
- Well, turn it off!

527
00:32:34,807 --> 00:32:37,685
Come on, will you?
Let the girls have their music?

528
00:32:38,167 --> 00:32:39,486
Stanley!

529
00:32:45,967 --> 00:32:48,606
There you are.
I didn't hear you name it!

530
00:32:48,767 --> 00:32:50,564
- Didn't I name it?
- I wasn't listening.

531
00:32:50,727 --> 00:32:51,716
What were you doing?

532
00:32:52,047 --> 00:32:53,366
Looking through the drapes.

533
00:32:53,527 --> 00:32:55,757
- I was looking through no drapes.
- We're gonna play.

534
00:32:55,927 --> 00:32:58,157
We're gonna deal this hand again,
play cards or quit.

535
00:32:58,327 --> 00:32:59,396
Deal me out.

536
00:32:59,687 --> 00:33:02,326
All right, this game's gonna be
Spit in the Ocean.

537
00:33:10,887 --> 00:33:12,240
Yes?

538
00:33:13,527 --> 00:33:14,960
Hello.

539
00:33:19,247 --> 00:33:20,680
Excuse me.

540
00:33:21,047 --> 00:33:24,039
The little boy's room
is occupied right now.

541
00:33:24,247 --> 00:33:25,839
Oh, excuse me.

542
00:33:26,007 --> 00:33:29,204
- Have you got any cigs?
- Oh, sure.

543
00:33:30,887 --> 00:33:33,196
Oh, what a... What a pretty case.

544
00:33:33,367 --> 00:33:35,085
- Silver?
- Yes.

545
00:33:35,247 --> 00:33:36,760
Yes, read the inscription.

546
00:33:36,927 --> 00:33:38,963
Oh, there is an inscription.

547
00:33:39,127 --> 00:33:41,277
Why, I can't make it out.

548
00:33:45,087 --> 00:33:48,159
"And if God choose...

549
00:33:48,967 --> 00:33:52,243
...I shall but love thee better
after death."

550
00:33:52,407 --> 00:33:55,126
Why, that's from my
favorite sonnet by Mrs. Browning.

551
00:33:55,287 --> 00:33:57,198
- Why, you know it.
- Certainly, I do.

552
00:33:57,367 --> 00:34:00,040
Well, there's a story connected
with this inscription.

553
00:34:00,207 --> 00:34:01,606
It sounds like a romance.

554
00:34:01,767 --> 00:34:04,884
No, no, it's a pretty sad one.
The girl's dead now.

555
00:34:05,407 --> 00:34:09,320
She knew she was dying when she give
me this. A very strange girl, very sweet.

556
00:34:09,487 --> 00:34:12,684
- Very...
- She must have been very fond of you.

557
00:34:12,847 --> 00:34:15,600
Sick people have such
deep, sincere attachments.

558
00:34:15,767 --> 00:34:18,998
- That's right. They certainly do.
- Sorrow makes for sincerity, I think.

559
00:34:19,167 --> 00:34:20,680
It sure brings it out in people.

560
00:34:20,847 --> 00:34:23,759
The little there is belongs to people
who have known some sorrow.

561
00:34:23,927 --> 00:34:26,646
- I believe you're right about that.
- Oh, I'm positive I am.

562
00:34:26,807 --> 00:34:30,720
- Hey, Mitch!
- Deal me out. I'm talking to Miss...?

563
00:34:32,407 --> 00:34:33,840
DuBois.

564
00:34:34,367 --> 00:34:35,561
DuBois.

565
00:34:35,727 --> 00:34:37,365
It's a French name.

566
00:34:37,527 --> 00:34:39,563
It means "woods,"
and Blanche means "white"...

567
00:34:39,727 --> 00:34:41,638
...so the two together mean
"white woods"...

568
00:34:41,807 --> 00:34:43,365
...like an orchard in spring.

569
00:34:43,527 --> 00:34:45,404
You can remember it by that...

570
00:34:45,567 --> 00:34:46,920
...if you care to.

571
00:34:47,487 --> 00:34:49,205
You are Stella's sister, are you not?

572
00:34:49,367 --> 00:34:51,801
Yes. Stella is my precious little sister.

573
00:34:52,087 --> 00:34:55,284
I call her little in spite of the fact
that she's somewhat older than I am.

574
00:34:57,047 --> 00:35:00,517
Oh, just slightly. Less than a year.
Will you do something for me?

575
00:35:00,687 --> 00:35:01,836
Sure. Yes, what?

576
00:35:02,007 --> 00:35:05,522
I bought this adorable little paper lantern
at a Chinese shop on Bourbon.

577
00:35:05,687 --> 00:35:07,643
Put it over the light bulb.
Will you, please?

578
00:35:07,807 --> 00:35:09,160
I'd be glad to.

579
00:35:09,327 --> 00:35:13,206
I can't stand a naked light bulb
any more than I can a rude remark...

580
00:35:13,367 --> 00:35:15,005
...or a vulgar action.

581
00:35:15,167 --> 00:35:18,842
Well, I guess we strike you as being
a pretty rough bunch.

582
00:35:19,767 --> 00:35:22,406
I'm very adaptable to circumstances.

583
00:35:22,567 --> 00:35:24,558
Well, that's a good way to be.

584
00:35:26,847 --> 00:35:28,405
- You're not...?
- Married?

585
00:35:28,567 --> 00:35:31,604
Oh, no.
No, I'm an old maid schoolteacher.

586
00:35:31,967 --> 00:35:35,164
You may be a schoolteacher,
but you're certainly not an old maid.

587
00:35:36,567 --> 00:35:38,239
Why, thank you, sir.

588
00:35:38,407 --> 00:35:40,875
I appreciate your gallantry.

589
00:35:42,967 --> 00:35:45,037
So you're in the teaching profession.

590
00:35:45,367 --> 00:35:46,766
Yes.

591
00:35:47,447 --> 00:35:49,085
- Yes.
- Grade school or high school...?

592
00:35:49,247 --> 00:35:51,522
- Hey, Mitch!
- Coming!

593
00:35:51,687 --> 00:35:53,518
Gracious, what lung power.

594
00:35:53,687 --> 00:35:55,279
I teach high school in Auriol.

595
00:35:56,367 --> 00:35:57,959
Well, what do you teach?
What subject?

596
00:35:58,127 --> 00:36:02,040
- You guess.
- Well, I bet you teach art or music.

597
00:36:02,727 --> 00:36:05,036
Well, of course, I could be wrong.

598
00:36:05,207 --> 00:36:06,640
You might teach arithmetic.

599
00:36:06,807 --> 00:36:09,162
Never arithmetic, sir.
Never arithmetic.

600
00:36:09,327 --> 00:36:11,443
I don't know
my multiplication tables. Nope.

601
00:36:11,607 --> 00:36:13,916
I have the misfortune
of being an English instructor.

602
00:36:14,087 --> 00:36:16,396
I attempt to instill
a bunch of bobbysoxers...

603
00:36:16,567 --> 00:36:19,639
...and drugstore Romeos
with a reverence for Hawthorne...

604
00:36:19,807 --> 00:36:21,365
...and Whitman and Poe.

605
00:36:21,527 --> 00:36:24,087
Well, I bet some of them
are more interested in other things.

606
00:36:24,247 --> 00:36:26,044
How very right you are.

607
00:36:26,207 --> 00:36:29,995
Their literary heritage is not
what they treasure above all else.

608
00:36:30,167 --> 00:36:31,566
But they're sweet things...

609
00:36:31,727 --> 00:36:36,801
...and in the spring it's touching to see
them making their first discovery of love...

610
00:36:36,967 --> 00:36:41,040
...as if nobody had ever known it before.

611
00:36:43,807 --> 00:36:48,164
- Sorry. Oh, excuse me, excuse me.
- Have you finished?

612
00:36:48,327 --> 00:36:52,605
- Oh, yes. Yes, I have.
- Wait, wait. I'll turn on the radio.

613
00:36:54,527 --> 00:36:56,722
Turn on the light above now.

614
00:36:57,727 --> 00:36:59,285
Oh, look.

615
00:36:59,447 --> 00:37:02,007
We've made enchantment.

616
00:37:12,327 --> 00:37:16,286
- Three bullets, mustache.
- Straight! I gotcha!

617
00:37:17,807 --> 00:37:21,038
Stanley! Stanley!
What are you doing with the radio?

618
00:37:22,607 --> 00:37:24,404
Drunk! Drunk animal thing!

619
00:37:24,967 --> 00:37:26,161
- Get out!
- Hey!

620
00:37:26,327 --> 00:37:28,397
- Go on, get out!
- Hey!

621
00:37:29,207 --> 00:37:30,845
Let go of her!

622
00:37:31,007 --> 00:37:33,202
My sister is gonna have a baby!

623
00:37:38,127 --> 00:37:39,958
You come on up to my place, honey.

624
00:37:40,127 --> 00:37:42,482
Sister, did he hurt you, darling?

625
00:37:42,687 --> 00:37:45,997
Poker should not be played
in a house with women.

626
00:37:46,767 --> 00:37:48,917
- All right, take it easy, will you?
- Look out.

627
00:37:50,407 --> 00:37:52,796
Get him in that shower.

628
00:37:53,327 --> 00:37:55,921
- Look out.
- Get him in that shower, I said!

629
00:37:56,087 --> 00:37:58,521
Come on, all right.
Get his feet, will you? Get his feet!

630
00:37:58,687 --> 00:38:00,757
Grab his feet, come on, take it easy.

631
00:38:00,927 --> 00:38:02,724
Come on, boy. Get under there.

632
00:38:02,887 --> 00:38:04,400
Come on.

633
00:38:04,727 --> 00:38:06,524
Get under there. There you go.

634
00:38:08,567 --> 00:38:10,478
How do you feel, Stan?

635
00:38:10,967 --> 00:38:13,527
Stanley, wake up!
Hey, Stanley!

636
00:38:13,687 --> 00:38:18,078
- We ought to get his clothes off and...
- Hey! What do you think...!

637
00:38:23,807 --> 00:38:26,526
Poker should not be played
in a house with women!

638
00:38:26,687 --> 00:38:28,405
Come on!

639
00:38:30,167 --> 00:38:31,919
- Hey!
- Where's Steve? Come on.

640
00:38:32,087 --> 00:38:33,918
Wait. Come here. Take it easy.

641
00:38:46,247 --> 00:38:47,646
Stella.

642
00:38:52,007 --> 00:38:53,520
Stella.

643
00:38:56,567 --> 00:38:58,000
Honey?

644
00:38:59,447 --> 00:39:01,244
Hey, Stella?

645
00:39:03,887 --> 00:39:05,798
Honey, where are you?

646
00:39:08,407 --> 00:39:09,886
Stella?

647
00:39:18,647 --> 00:39:20,558
Hey, baby...

648
00:39:31,127 --> 00:39:34,244
Look, you can sleep over here, Stella.
Blanche can have Steve's place.

649
00:39:34,407 --> 00:39:37,046
He ain't coming home tonight
if he knows what's good for him.

650
00:39:37,647 --> 00:39:40,081
<i>Is my baby up there?</i>
<i>I want her...</i>

651
00:39:40,247 --> 00:39:43,205
Look, she ain't coming down
and she ain't gonna talk to you neither...

652
00:39:43,367 --> 00:39:45,597
...so you might just as well
not call her!

653
00:39:52,727 --> 00:39:55,480
Hey, Stella!

654
00:39:55,647 --> 00:39:57,638
You quit that howling down there
and go to bed!

655
00:39:57,807 --> 00:40:00,526
- Eunice, I want my girl down here!
- You shut up!

656
00:40:00,687 --> 00:40:02,439
- You're gonna get the law on you.
- Stella!

657
00:40:02,607 --> 00:40:04,916
You can't beat on a woman
and then call her back.

658
00:40:05,087 --> 00:40:06,156
You're gonna have a baby.

659
00:40:06,327 --> 00:40:09,285
I hope they haul you in, turn a fire hose
on you like the last time!

660
00:40:09,447 --> 00:40:11,642
- I want my girl down here!
- You stinker!

661
00:40:16,327 --> 00:40:19,717
Hey, Stella!

662
00:40:21,327 --> 00:40:24,319
Hey, Stella!

663
00:40:33,767 --> 00:40:35,962
I wouldn't mix in this.

664
00:41:34,647 --> 00:41:37,081
Don't ever leave me, baby.

665
00:41:52,727 --> 00:41:54,604
Blanche, come back!

666
00:42:19,847 --> 00:42:21,405
Miss DuBois?

667
00:42:22,007 --> 00:42:23,599
Miss DuBois?

668
00:42:27,047 --> 00:42:29,197
All quiet along the Potomac now?

669
00:42:29,447 --> 00:42:31,642
She ran down here
and went back in there with him.

670
00:42:31,887 --> 00:42:33,286
- Sure she did.
- I'm terrified.

671
00:42:33,447 --> 00:42:36,041
Nothing to be scared of.
They're crazy about each other.

672
00:42:36,207 --> 00:42:38,323
It's a shame this had to happen
when you got here.

673
00:42:38,487 --> 00:42:40,239
- Violence is so...
- Sit down on the steps...

674
00:42:40,407 --> 00:42:42,477
...and have a cigarette with me.
- Why...

675
00:42:42,647 --> 00:42:44,046
...I'm not properly dressed.

676
00:42:44,207 --> 00:42:46,596
Well, that don't make no difference
in the Quarter.

677
00:42:47,487 --> 00:42:50,638
Such a pretty silver case.

678
00:42:50,807 --> 00:42:53,082
I showed you the inscription, didn't I?

679
00:42:53,247 --> 00:42:54,475
Yes.

680
00:43:00,007 --> 00:43:01,679
So much...

681
00:43:01,847 --> 00:43:04,998
So much confusion in the world.

682
00:43:06,647 --> 00:43:09,036
Thank you for being so kind.

683
00:43:09,207 --> 00:43:11,926
I need kindness now.

684
00:43:18,567 --> 00:43:21,764
Bananas!

685
00:43:22,447 --> 00:43:25,962
Bananas!

686
00:43:33,127 --> 00:43:34,606
Stella?

687
00:43:38,967 --> 00:43:42,164
Stella. Oh, my baby.
My baby sister.

688
00:43:42,327 --> 00:43:44,283
Why, angel,
what's the matter with you?

689
00:43:44,487 --> 00:43:46,603
- He left?
- Stan?

690
00:43:46,767 --> 00:43:47,961
Will he be back?

691
00:43:48,167 --> 00:43:50,283
- He's gone to get the car greased, why?
- Why?

692
00:43:50,487 --> 00:43:53,923
I've been half-crazy, Stella. How could
you come back to this place last night?

693
00:43:54,087 --> 00:43:57,602
Please, Blanche. He was as good
as a lamb when I came back.

694
00:43:57,767 --> 00:44:01,043
- He's really very ashamed of himself.
- And that...

695
00:44:01,247 --> 00:44:03,442
- That makes it all right?
- No.

696
00:44:04,087 --> 00:44:06,760
Stanley's always smashed things.

697
00:44:07,247 --> 00:44:10,523
On our wedding night,
as soon as we came in here...

698
00:44:10,727 --> 00:44:12,445
...he snatched off one of my slippers...

699
00:44:12,607 --> 00:44:15,360
...and rushed about the place smashing
the light bulbs with it.

700
00:44:15,527 --> 00:44:17,324
He did what?

701
00:44:18,567 --> 00:44:21,525
He smashed all the light bulbs
with the heel of my slipper.

702
00:44:21,767 --> 00:44:23,962
And you let him?
Didn't run, didn't scream?

703
00:44:25,447 --> 00:44:28,405
I was sort of thrilled by it.

704
00:44:29,447 --> 00:44:31,244
Eunice and you had breakfast?

705
00:44:31,607 --> 00:44:34,326
Oh, do you suppose
I wanted any breakfast?

706
00:44:34,487 --> 00:44:37,126
You're so matter-of-fact
about it all, Stella.

707
00:44:37,647 --> 00:44:39,763
What other can I be?

708
