00:59:59,607 --> 01:00:01,563
...and sweetly on your mouth.

958
01:00:13,207 --> 01:00:14,640
Run away now, quickly.

959
01:00:15,047 --> 01:00:17,402
It'd be nice to keep you
but I've got to be good...

960
01:00:17,567 --> 01:00:19,444
...and keep my hands off children.

961
01:00:31,167 --> 01:00:32,600
Why, look who's here.

962
01:00:32,887 --> 01:00:34,923
My <i>Rosenkavalier.</i>

963
01:00:36,407 --> 01:00:38,967
Oh, bow to me first.

964
01:00:41,367 --> 01:00:43,801
Now, <i>prsentez.</i>

965
01:01:04,807 --> 01:01:06,399
Hiya, Mitch.

966
01:01:13,487 --> 01:01:16,763
I'm afraid you haven't had much
fun out of this evening, Blanche.

967
01:01:16,967 --> 01:01:19,879
- I spoiled it for you.
- No, you didn't.

968
01:01:20,047 --> 01:01:23,244
I simply couldn't rise
to the occasion, that was all.

969
01:01:23,407 --> 01:01:27,286
I don't think I've ever tried so hard to be
gay and made such a dismal mess of it.

970
01:01:27,447 --> 01:01:30,883
I get ten points for trying.
I did try.

971
01:01:34,487 --> 01:01:36,079
Hello, moon.

972
01:01:37,767 --> 01:01:39,325
I'm looking for the Pleiades...

973
01:01:39,487 --> 01:01:40,761
...the Seven Sisters...

974
01:01:40,927 --> 01:01:42,804
...but these girls aren't out tonight.

975
01:01:43,007 --> 01:01:44,406
Oh, yes, they are.

976
01:01:44,567 --> 01:01:46,159
There they are, God bless them.

977
01:01:46,327 --> 01:01:48,887
All in a bunch, going home
from their little bridge party.

978
01:01:49,047 --> 01:01:50,719
May I kiss you?

979
01:01:50,887 --> 01:01:52,843
Why do you always ask me if you may?

980
01:01:53,007 --> 01:01:56,204
- I don't know if you want me to or not.
- Why should you be so doubtful?

981
01:01:56,407 --> 01:01:58,159
We parked by the lake,
and I kissed you...

982
01:01:58,327 --> 01:02:01,319
Honey, it wasn't the kiss I objected to.
I liked the kiss very much.

983
01:02:01,487 --> 01:02:04,559
It was the other little familiarity
that I felt obliged to discourage.

984
01:02:04,727 --> 01:02:06,683
Not that I resented it,
not a bit in the world.

985
01:02:06,887 --> 01:02:10,163
In fact, I was somewhat flattered
that you desired me.

986
01:02:10,367 --> 01:02:14,042
But you know as well as I do that
a single girl, a girl alone in the world...

987
01:02:14,247 --> 01:02:16,363
...has got to keep a firm hold
on her emotions...

988
01:02:16,527 --> 01:02:19,360
...or she'll be lost.
- Lost?

989
01:02:19,527 --> 01:02:23,042
I guess you're used to the type of girl
that likes to be lost.

990
01:02:23,767 --> 01:02:26,964
I like you to be exactly
the way that you are...

991
01:02:27,447 --> 01:02:30,564
...because in all my experience,
I have never known anyone like you.

992
01:02:36,327 --> 01:02:38,124
Are you laughing at me?

993
01:02:40,407 --> 01:02:41,760
No.

994
01:02:41,967 --> 01:02:43,559
No, honey.

995
01:02:43,967 --> 01:02:45,923
I'm not laughing at you.

996
01:02:47,447 --> 01:02:50,723
Well, come on,
let's finish our nightcap.

997
01:02:50,887 --> 01:02:52,923
You've been so anxious and solemn
all evening.

998
01:02:53,087 --> 01:02:54,964
We've both been anxious and solemn.

999
01:02:55,127 --> 01:02:58,244
And now for these last few remaining
moments of our lives together...

1000
01:02:58,407 --> 01:03:00,363
...I want to create <i>joie de vivre.</i>

1001
01:03:03,567 --> 01:03:05,523
I'm lighting this candle.

1002
01:03:06,807 --> 01:03:08,001
That's good.

1003
01:03:08,167 --> 01:03:10,123
We're going to be very bohemian.

1004
01:03:10,327 --> 01:03:14,923
We are gonna pretend we're sitting in an
artists' cafe on the Left Bank in Paris.

1005
01:03:18,767 --> 01:03:21,884
- Understand French?
- No, no, I don't understand French.

1006
01:03:22,607 --> 01:03:26,202
Well, why don't you sit down.
Take off your coat. Loosen your collar.

1007
01:03:26,407 --> 01:03:29,524
- No, I better leave it on.
- No. I want you to be comfortable.

1008
01:03:29,687 --> 01:03:32,804
No, I'm ashamed of the way I perspire.
My shirt is sticking to me.

1009
01:03:33,007 --> 01:03:37,603
Perspiration is healthy. If people didn't
perspire, they would die in five minutes.

1010
01:03:37,767 --> 01:03:40,042
Oh, this is a nice coat.
What...?

1011
01:03:40,247 --> 01:03:43,159
- What material is it?
- They call this stuff alpaca.

1012
01:03:43,327 --> 01:03:46,160
- Oh, alpaca.
- It's very lightweight alpaca.

1013
01:03:46,447 --> 01:03:49,041
- Oh, lightweight alpaca.
- Yes.

1014
01:03:49,207 --> 01:03:52,722
I don't like to wear a watch coat even in
the summer because I sweat through it.

1015
01:03:52,887 --> 01:03:54,320
And it don't look neat on me.

1016
01:03:54,487 --> 01:03:58,321
A man with a heavy build is careful of
what he wears so he don't look clumsy.

1017
01:03:58,487 --> 01:04:01,445
- Why, you're not too heavy.
- You don't think I am?

1018
01:04:01,607 --> 01:04:03,359
You're not the delicate type.

1019
01:04:03,527 --> 01:04:07,759
You have a massive bone structure
and a very imposing physique.

1020
01:04:08,767 --> 01:04:10,405
I thank you.

1021
01:04:11,127 --> 01:04:14,244
At Christmas, I was given a membership
to the New Orleans Sports Club.

1022
01:04:14,447 --> 01:04:17,564
- Oh, good.
- It's the finest present I was ever given.

1023
01:04:18,127 --> 01:04:22,166
I work out there with the weights
and I swim. I keep myself fit.

1024
01:04:22,327 --> 01:04:25,603
When I started there I was soft
in the belly, but now my belly is hard.

1025
01:04:25,767 --> 01:04:29,282
It's so hard now a man can punch me
in the belly and it don't hurt me.

1026
01:04:30,207 --> 01:04:33,324
Punch me.
Go ahead. Go on. Punch.

1027
01:04:33,527 --> 01:04:34,846
Come on.

1028
01:04:35,767 --> 01:04:38,486
- Gracious.
- See?

1029
01:04:38,647 --> 01:04:39,966
Blanche.

1030
01:04:40,127 --> 01:04:41,685
Blanche.

1031
01:04:42,007 --> 01:04:43,406
Guess how much I weigh?

1032
01:04:43,927 --> 01:04:49,126
- I'd say in the vicinity of 180 pounds.
- No, guess again.

1033
01:04:49,287 --> 01:04:50,686
- Not so much?
- No, more.

1034
01:04:50,847 --> 01:04:53,486
- Well?
- I weigh 207 pounds.

1035
01:04:53,647 --> 01:04:55,842
I'm 6' 1 " and one-half inches tall
in my bare feet...

1036
01:04:56,047 --> 01:04:58,322
...without shoes on,
and that's what I weigh stripped.

1037
01:04:58,647 --> 01:05:02,322
Oh, my goodness, it's awe-inspiring.

1038
01:05:03,447 --> 01:05:06,166
Well, my weight's not a very
interesting subject to talk about.

1039
01:05:06,327 --> 01:05:07,919
What's yours?

1040
01:05:08,727 --> 01:05:10,001
- My weight?
- Yes.

1041
01:05:10,167 --> 01:05:12,362
- You guess.
- Let me lift you.

1042
01:05:12,647 --> 01:05:16,322
Samson. Go on, lift me!

1043
01:05:18,247 --> 01:05:21,683
- Why, you're light as a feather.
- You may release me now.

1044
01:05:22,007 --> 01:05:24,680
I said unhand me, sir.

1045
01:05:24,847 --> 01:05:28,442
Mitch, Mitch, we're in public.
You must behave like a gentleman.

1046
01:05:28,607 --> 01:05:30,723
Just give me a slap
whenever I step out of bounds.

1047
01:05:30,927 --> 01:05:35,523
It won't be necessary. You're a natural
gentleman. One of the few left.

1048
01:05:35,687 --> 01:05:39,282
I don't want you to think that I'm
severe or old-maid schoolteacherish...

1049
01:05:39,447 --> 01:05:41,244
...or anything. It's just, well, l...

1050
01:05:41,447 --> 01:05:45,679
I guess I have old-fashioned ideals.

1051
01:05:58,967 --> 01:06:01,083
Where's Stanley and Stella tonight?

1052
01:06:01,247 --> 01:06:04,284
I think they were planning
to take in a midnight preview.

1053
01:06:04,447 --> 01:06:06,722
We all ought to go out together
some night.

1054
01:06:08,207 --> 01:06:10,243
That wouldn't be a good plan.

1055
01:06:10,447 --> 01:06:11,800
Why not?

1056
01:06:12,167 --> 01:06:14,442
You are an old friend of Stanley's?

1057
01:06:14,647 --> 01:06:16,524
We was together in the 241 st.

1058
01:06:16,727 --> 01:06:19,924
- I guess he talks to you pretty frankly.
- Sure.

1059
01:06:20,127 --> 01:06:22,243
Has he talked to you about me?

1060
01:06:23,927 --> 01:06:25,565
- No, not much.
- The way you say that...

1061
01:06:25,727 --> 01:06:27,763
...I suspect that he has.
- He hasn't said much.

1062
01:06:27,967 --> 01:06:31,721
Well, what he has said, what would
you say his attitude toward me was?

1063
01:06:31,887 --> 01:06:33,525
- What makes you ask that?
- Well...

1064
01:06:33,687 --> 01:06:35,643
Don't you get along with him?

1065
01:06:36,087 --> 01:06:37,600
What do you think?

1066
01:06:37,767 --> 01:06:39,723
I think he don't understand you.

1067
01:06:40,247 --> 01:06:44,843
That's putting it mildly. Surely he must
have told you how much he hates me.

1068
01:06:49,207 --> 01:06:50,845
I don't think he hates you.

1069
01:06:51,007 --> 01:06:54,124
He hates me,
or why would he insult me?

1070
01:06:54,447 --> 01:06:55,641
Of course...

1071
01:06:55,807 --> 01:06:58,560
...there is such a thing as
the hostility of...

1072
01:06:58,727 --> 01:07:03,243
Perhaps in some strange
kind of way, he...

1073
01:07:05,847 --> 01:07:07,485
To think of it makes me...

1074
01:07:07,647 --> 01:07:10,286
- Blanche.
- Yes, honey?

1075
01:07:10,447 --> 01:07:14,201
- Blanche, can I ask you a question?
- Yes, what?

1076
01:07:14,767 --> 01:07:16,280
How old are you?

1077
01:07:17,887 --> 01:07:21,004
What do you want to know that for?

1078
01:07:21,167 --> 01:07:25,285
I talked to my mother about you
and she said, "How old is Blanche?"

1079
01:07:26,167 --> 01:07:29,603
- You talked to your mother about me?
- Yes.

1080
01:07:29,767 --> 01:07:31,246
Why?

1081
01:07:31,607 --> 01:07:34,804
Because I told her how nice
you were, and I liked you.

1082
01:07:35,687 --> 01:07:38,679
Were you sincere about that?

1083
01:07:39,687 --> 01:07:42,121
You know I was.

1084
01:07:42,647 --> 01:07:46,162
Why did your mother
want to know my age?

1085
01:07:46,367 --> 01:07:50,565
- My mother is sick, and...
- Oh, I'm sorry to hear it. Badly?

1086
01:07:50,887 --> 01:07:52,684
She won't live long...

1087
01:07:52,887 --> 01:07:56,323
...maybe just a few months,
and she worries because I'm not settled.

1088
01:07:56,487 --> 01:07:59,285
She wants to see me
settled down before she...

1089
01:08:02,647 --> 01:08:05,639
You love her very much, don't you?

1090
01:08:07,927 --> 01:08:11,203
You'll be lonely when she passes on,
won't you?

1091
01:08:15,127 --> 01:08:17,402
I know what that means.

1092
01:08:19,887 --> 01:08:21,559
To be lonely?

1093
01:08:22,687 --> 01:08:24,882
I loved someone once.

1094
01:08:25,047 --> 01:08:27,800
And the person I loved, I lost.

1095
01:08:29,007 --> 01:08:30,326
Dead?

1096
01:08:34,007 --> 01:08:35,804
He was a boy.

1097
01:08:36,567 --> 01:08:39,684
Just a boy,
when I was a very young girl.

1098
01:08:40,367 --> 01:08:43,120
When I was 16, I made the discovery:

1099
01:08:43,287 --> 01:08:44,845
Love.

1100
01:08:45,327 --> 01:08:47,124
All at once, and much...

1101
01:08:47,287 --> 01:08:49,562
...much too completely.

1102
01:08:49,847 --> 01:08:53,123
It was like you suddenly turned
a blinding light...

1103
01:08:53,327 --> 01:08:56,922
...on something that had
always been half in shadow.

1104
01:08:57,327 --> 01:09:00,285
That's how it struck the world for me.

1105
01:09:00,607 --> 01:09:02,484
But I was unlucky.

1106
01:09:02,687 --> 01:09:04,279
Deluded.

1107
01:09:05,247 --> 01:09:07,761
There was something about the boy.

1108
01:09:07,927 --> 01:09:10,487
A nervousness, a tenderness...

1109
01:09:10,647 --> 01:09:12,319
...an uncertainty.

1110
01:09:12,487 --> 01:09:14,523
And I didn't understand.

1111
01:09:15,007 --> 01:09:19,000
I didn't understand why this boy,
who wrote poetry...

1112
01:09:19,167 --> 01:09:21,522
...didn't seem able to do anything else.

1113
01:09:21,727 --> 01:09:23,683
He lost every job.

1114
01:09:24,567 --> 01:09:26,603
He came to me for help.

1115
01:09:26,767 --> 01:09:28,439
I didn't know that.

1116
01:09:29,007 --> 01:09:30,963
I didn't know anything...

1117
01:09:31,127 --> 01:09:33,243
...except that I loved him...

1118
01:09:33,527 --> 01:09:35,279
...unendurably.

1119
01:09:36,167 --> 01:09:38,522
At night I pretended to sleep.

1120
01:09:39,127 --> 01:09:40,719
I heard him crying.

1121
01:09:41,687 --> 01:09:43,120
Crying.

1122
01:09:45,847 --> 01:09:48,725
Crying the way a lost child cries.

1123
01:09:49,527 --> 01:09:50,801
I don't understand.

1124
01:09:51,767 --> 01:09:53,200
No.

1125
01:09:54,967 --> 01:09:57,083
No, neither did I.

1126
01:09:58,127 --> 01:10:00,083
And that's why I...

1127
01:10:01,367 --> 01:10:03,403
I killed him.

1128
01:10:04,887 --> 01:10:06,206
You...?

1129
01:10:15,607 --> 01:10:17,165
One night...

1130
01:10:17,567 --> 01:10:21,082
...we drove out to a place
called Moon Lake Casino.

1131
01:10:21,687 --> 01:10:24,360
We danced the Varsouviana.

1132
01:10:24,567 --> 01:10:28,560
Suddenly, in the middle of the dance,
the boy I married broke away from me...

1133
01:10:28,727 --> 01:10:30,399
...and ran out of the casino.

1134
01:10:30,607 --> 01:10:32,165
A few minutes later...

1135
01:10:32,327 --> 01:10:33,885
...a shot.

1136
01:10:34,647 --> 01:10:36,046
I ran.

1137
01:10:36,207 --> 01:10:37,560
All did.

1138
01:10:37,727 --> 01:10:41,322
All ran and gathered about
the terrible thing at the edge of the lake.

1139
01:10:48,887 --> 01:10:51,560
He'd stuck a revolver into his mouth...

1140
01:10:51,727 --> 01:10:53,206
...and fired.

1141
01:10:58,567 --> 01:11:00,603
It was because...

1142
01:11:00,847 --> 01:11:02,803
...on the dance floor...

1143
01:11:03,047 --> 01:11:06,084
...unable to stop myself, I'd said:

1144
01:11:06,647 --> 01:11:08,319
"You're weak.

1145
01:11:08,567 --> 01:11:11,001
I've lost respect for you.

1146
01:11:11,727 --> 01:11:14,161
I despise you."

1147
01:11:19,327 --> 01:11:20,726
And then...

1148
01:11:22,167 --> 01:11:25,523
...the searchlight
which had been turned on the world...

1149
01:11:25,727 --> 01:11:27,843
...was turned off again.

1150
01:11:28,167 --> 01:11:29,566
And never...

1151
01:11:29,727 --> 01:11:34,243
...for one moment since,
has there been any light stronger than...

1152
01:11:35,087 --> 01:11:36,566
Than this...

1153
01:11:37,127 --> 01:11:39,004
...yellow lantern.

1154
01:11:54,407 --> 01:11:56,363
You need somebody.

1155
01:11:57,127 --> 01:11:59,322
And I need somebody too.

1156
01:12:05,767 --> 01:12:08,122
Could it be you and me, Blanche?

1157
01:12:23,767 --> 01:12:25,644
Sometimes...

1158
01:12:26,447 --> 01:12:28,403
...there's God...

1159
01:12:29,527 --> 01:12:31,643
...so quickly.

1160
01:12:35,487 --> 01:12:39,844
You wanna mess with me, sonny boy,
come on! All right, turn him loose!

1161
01:12:40,047 --> 01:12:43,244
You're gonna kill who? You don't even
know when you're getting wised up.

1162
01:12:43,607 --> 01:12:45,165
You don't have to wise me up!

1163
01:12:45,327 --> 01:12:48,683
Come on, here. Come on,
get to work here. We gotta get going.

1164
01:12:48,847 --> 01:12:50,485
We got some bucks
to make around here.

1165
01:12:50,647 --> 01:12:52,524
Go ahead and marry her,
but hurry it up.

1166
01:12:52,687 --> 01:12:55,281
She's been in my house
five months and her time is up.

1167
01:13:26,647 --> 01:13:28,444
Hello, Stanley.

1168
01:13:36,127 --> 01:13:38,243
Some canary bird.

1169
01:13:39,527 --> 01:13:41,040
All right.

1170
01:13:41,207 --> 01:13:45,246
Please tell me quietly just what you think
you found out about my sister.

1171
01:13:45,407 --> 01:13:48,080
You know your sister Blanche
is no lily, don't you?

1172
01:13:48,247 --> 01:13:50,283
What have you heard,
and who from?

1173
01:13:50,487 --> 01:13:53,001
You should know the line
that she's been feeding to Mitch.

1174
01:13:53,167 --> 01:13:56,079
Our supply man at the plant's
been going through Auriol for years.

1175
01:13:56,247 --> 01:13:57,760
He knows all about her.

1176
01:13:57,927 --> 01:14:01,442
And everybody else in the town
of Auriol knows all about her.

1177
01:14:01,647 --> 01:14:05,162
She's as famous in Auriol as if she was
the president of the United States...

1178
01:14:05,367 --> 01:14:08,245
...only she's not respected by any party.

1179
01:14:16,527 --> 01:14:19,280
So she moved to a hotel
called the Flamingo...

1180
01:14:19,447 --> 01:14:21,642
...which is a second-class hotel...

1181
01:14:21,847 --> 01:14:23,599
...and has the advantages...

1182
01:14:23,767 --> 01:14:27,601
...of not interfering with the private
and social life of the personalities there.

1183
01:14:27,767 --> 01:14:30,645
Now, the Flamingo is used to
all kinds of goings on.

1184
01:14:30,807 --> 01:14:35,119
But the management of the Flamingo
was impressed by Dame Blanche.

1185
01:14:35,287 --> 01:14:37,721
In fact, they were so impressed
that they requested her...

1186
01:14:37,887 --> 01:14:40,003
...to turn in her room key
for permanently.

1187
01:14:40,167 --> 01:14:43,842
And this happened a couple of weeks
before she showed here.

1188
01:14:50,647 --> 01:14:53,639
Honey, I know how
this is gonna upset you.

1189
01:14:53,807 --> 01:14:57,163
But listen, she pulled the wool
over your eyes just as much as Mitch's.

1190
01:14:57,367 --> 01:14:59,164
Pure invention.
Not a word of truth in it.

1191
01:14:59,367 --> 01:15:01,801
Baby, listen. I checked on every story.

1192
01:15:01,967 --> 01:15:05,482
The trouble was she couldn't
put on her act anymore in Auriol...

1193
01:15:05,647 --> 01:15:06,921
...because they wised up.

1194
01:15:07,087 --> 01:15:09,965
And after two, three days they quit,
so she goes on to another one.

1195
01:15:10,127 --> 01:15:12,641
The same old line, the same old act
and the same old hooey.

1196
01:15:12,807 --> 01:15:15,082
And as time went by,
she became the town character...

1197
01:15:15,287 --> 01:15:18,199
...regarded not just as different,
but downright loco and nuts.

1198
01:15:18,367 --> 01:15:20,722
Which brings us to lie number two...

1199
01:15:22,487 --> 01:15:24,045
Stella.

1200
01:15:25,207 --> 01:15:26,401
Baby, now...

1201
01:15:26,567 --> 01:15:30,003
She didn't resign temporarily because
of her nerves. She was kicked out...

1202
01:15:30,207 --> 01:15:32,163
...before the spring term ended.

1203
01:15:36,007 --> 01:15:38,680
And, now, I hate to tell you the reason
that step was taken.

1204
01:15:38,847 --> 01:15:41,202
A 17-year-old kid
she got mixed up with.

1205
01:15:41,367 --> 01:15:42,959
The boy's dad learned about it...

1206
01:15:43,127 --> 01:15:45,641
...and he got in touch
with the high school superintendent.

1207
01:15:45,807 --> 01:15:48,401
And it was practically a town ordinance
passed against her.

1208
01:15:48,567 --> 01:15:51,161
- Stella!
- Yes, Blanche?

1209
01:15:51,327 --> 01:15:54,285
Can I have another bath towel
to dry my hair with? I just washed it.

1210
01:15:54,447 --> 01:15:55,926
Yes, honey.

1211
01:16:00,327 --> 01:16:02,761
- What's the matter, honey?
- Matter, what?

1212
01:16:03,287 --> 01:16:05,642
You have such a strange
expression on your face.

1213
01:16:05,847 --> 01:16:08,441
- I guess I'm a little tired, is...
- Well...

1214
01:16:08,607 --> 01:16:10,962
...why don't you take a hot bath
as soon as I get out?

1215
01:16:11,447 --> 01:16:13,244
How soon is that gonna be, Blanche?

1216
01:16:13,407 --> 01:16:16,160
Not so terribly long,
possess your soul in patience.

1217
01:16:16,327 --> 01:16:18,363
It's not my soul I'm worried about.

1218
01:16:22,807 --> 01:16:24,240
Well?

1219
01:16:29,767 --> 01:16:31,564
How many candles
you sticking in the cake?

1220
01:16:32,087 --> 01:16:34,760
I stopped at 25.

1221
01:16:35,647 --> 01:16:37,399
You got company expected?

1222
01:16:37,567 --> 01:16:39,444
We asked Mitch to come over.

1223
01:16:39,607 --> 01:16:42,167
Well, don't expect Mitch
over here tonight.

1224
01:16:42,807 --> 01:16:44,081
Why?

1225
01:16:45,487 --> 01:16:49,446
Mitch is a buddy of mine.
We was together in the 241 st Engineers.

1226
01:16:49,607 --> 01:16:52,360
We work in the same plant,
we're on the same bowling team!

1227
01:16:52,527 --> 01:16:54,722
Stanley Kowalski, did you repeat
what that...?

1228
01:16:54,927 --> 01:16:57,441
You bet I told him.
I would have that on my conscience...

1229
01:16:57,607 --> 01:16:59,962
...if I knew all that
and let my best friend get caught.

1230
01:17:00,127 --> 01:17:02,163
- Is Mitch through with her?
- I don't know...

1231
01:17:02,367 --> 01:17:04,801
...but he's wised up.
- Mitch was gonna marry her!

1232
01:17:04,967 --> 01:17:06,719
He's not gonna marry her now!

1233
01:17:06,887 --> 01:17:09,242
He's not gonna jump into a tank
with a school of sharks.

1234
01:17:09,407 --> 01:17:13,844
- What'll she do? What will she do?
- Oh, her future is mapped out for her.

1235
01:17:14,647 --> 01:17:16,399
What do you mean?

1236
01:17:16,567 --> 01:17:21,163
Hey, toots! Canary bird,
will you get out of the bathroom!

1237
01:17:23,927 --> 01:17:26,441
I feel so good after a long, hot bath.

1238
01:17:26,607 --> 01:17:29,041
I feel so good and cool and rested.

1239
01:17:30,167 --> 01:17:33,045
- Do you, Blanche?
- Yes, I do. So refreshed.

1240
01:17:33,207 --> 01:17:35,402
Why, a hot bath
and a long, cold drink...

1241
01:17:35,607 --> 01:17:38,724
...always gives me
a brand-new outlook on life.

1242
01:17:40,327 --> 01:17:41,840
What's the matter?

1243
01:17:42,087 --> 01:17:43,884
What's happened.

1244
01:17:44,127 --> 01:17:47,881
- What is it?
- Nothing's happened, Blanche.

1245
01:17:48,327 --> 01:17:50,045
You're lying.

1246
01:17:50,607 --> 01:17:52,404
Something has.

1247
01:18:00,367 --> 01:18:01,925
Stanley?

1248
01:18:02,087 --> 01:18:03,600
Stanley, tell us a joke.

1249
01:18:03,767 --> 01:18:05,962
Tell us a funny little story
to make us all laugh.

1250
01:18:06,167 --> 01:18:08,362
I don't know what's the matter,
we're all so solemn.

1251
01:18:08,567 --> 01:18:10,444
Is it because I've been
stood up by my beau?

1252
01:18:10,647 --> 01:18:14,162
First time in my experience with men...
And I've had a good deal of all sorts.

1253
01:18:14,327 --> 01:18:15,999
- that I've been stood up by anyone.

1254
01:18:16,167 --> 01:18:17,680
I don't know how to take it.

1255
01:18:19,327 --> 01:18:21,124
Tell us a funny little story, Stanley.

1256
01:18:21,327 --> 01:18:23,522
Something to help us out.

1257
01:18:23,727 --> 01:18:25,922
I didn't think you liked
my stories, Blanche.

1258
01:18:26,087 --> 01:18:28,806
I like them when they're amusing,
but not indecent.

1259
01:18:28,967 --> 01:18:32,004
I don't know any refined enough
for your taste.

1260
01:18:33,327 --> 01:18:35,283
Well, then. Let me tell one.

1261
01:18:35,447 --> 01:18:38,200
Yes, tell one, Blanche.
You used to know a lot of good stories.

1262
01:18:38,967 --> 01:18:41,322
Now, let me see. I have to run
through my repertoire.

1263
01:18:41,527 --> 01:18:43,404
Oh, yes, I love parrot stories.

1264
01:18:43,567 --> 01:18:46,639
You all like parrot stories? This is about
the old maid and the parrot.

1265
01:18:46,807 --> 01:18:49,446
This old maid, she had a parrot
that cursed a blue streak...

1266
01:18:49,607 --> 01:18:52,724
...and knew more vulgar expressions
than Mr. Kowalski.

1267
01:18:53,327 --> 01:18:56,683
Well, the only way to hush the parrot up
was to put the cover...

1268
01:19:03,927 --> 01:19:05,724
Must be upstairs.

1269
01:19:06,887 --> 01:19:09,845
Well, the only way
to hush the parrot up was to put...

1270
01:19:10,407 --> 01:19:11,760
Go on, Blanche.

1271
01:19:13,047 --> 01:19:14,366
No.

1272
01:19:14,647 --> 01:19:16,842
I don't think
Mr. Kowalski will be amused.

1273
01:19:19,767 --> 01:19:23,442
Mr. Kowalski is too busy making
a pig of himself to think of anything else.

1274
01:19:24,127 --> 01:19:26,322
Your face and your fingers
are disgustingly greasy.

1275
01:19:26,527 --> 01:19:28,643
Go wash up
and then help me clear the table.

1276
01:19:38,287 --> 01:19:41,199
Now, that's how
I'm gonna clear the table.

1277
01:19:42,207 --> 01:19:45,324
Don't you ever talk that way to me.

1278
01:19:47,327 --> 01:19:51,240
Pig, Polack, disgusting, vulgar, greasy.

1279
01:19:51,927 --> 01:19:54,646
Those words have been on your tongue
and your sister's tongue...

1280
01:19:54,807 --> 01:19:56,559
...just too much around here.

1281
01:19:58,167 --> 01:20:00,522
Who do you think you are,
a pair of queens?

1282
01:20:00,687 --> 01:20:04,600
Remember Huey Long said: Every man's
a king, and I'm the king around here.

1283
01:20:04,767 --> 01:20:06,723
And don't you forget it.

1284
01:20:13,967 --> 01:20:17,403
My place is all cleared up now.
You want me to clear yours?

1285
01:20:26,487 --> 01:20:27,761
Stella...

1286
01:20:27,927 --> 01:20:29,724
...what happened while I was bathing?

1287
01:20:29,927 --> 01:20:34,079
- What did he tell you?
- Nothing. Nothing, nothing, Blanche.

1288
01:20:34,247 --> 01:20:36,920
- I think he told you about Mitch and me.
- No.

1289
01:20:37,087 --> 01:20:39,282
You know why Mitch didn't come,
but you won't tell.

1290
01:20:39,447 --> 01:20:41,483
- No.
- I'm gonna call him.

1291
01:20:41,687 --> 01:20:44,759
- Don't call him!
- Yes, I am. I'll call him on the phone.

1292
01:20:45,487 --> 01:20:46,840
Blanche, I wouldn't call him.

1293
01:20:47,007 --> 01:20:49,805
Got to be given some explanation
from someone.

1294
01:20:54,687 --> 01:20:56,962
Well, I hope you're pleased
with your doings.

1295
01:20:57,887 --> 01:21:01,323
I never had so much trouble
swallowing food in my life...

1296
01:21:01,767 --> 01:21:04,600
...Iooking at that girl's face
and that empty chair.

1297
01:21:04,767 --> 01:21:08,521
Hello? I want to talk
to Mr. Mitchell, please.

1298
01:21:10,887 --> 01:21:12,684
I'd like to leave a number, if I may.

1299
01:21:12,887 --> 01:21:15,606
- Honey.
- Tulane-4947.

1300
01:21:15,767 --> 01:21:18,201
And say it's important to call, please.

1301
01:21:18,407 --> 01:21:23,083
Honey, it's gonna be all right after
she goes and after you have the baby.

1302
01:21:23,367 --> 01:21:26,484
It's gonna be all right again
between you and me, the way it was.

1303
01:21:26,687 --> 01:21:28,564
Remember how it was?

1304
01:21:28,967 --> 01:21:32,084
It's gonna be so sweet when we can
get them colored lights going...

1305
01:21:32,247 --> 01:21:35,205
...with nobody's sister
behind the curtains to hear us.

1306
01:21:46,367 --> 01:21:48,722
Steve and Eunice.

1307
01:21:50,927 --> 01:21:53,521
Come on back in.

1308
01:21:55,607 --> 01:21:57,199
Blanche?

1309
01:21:58,127 --> 01:21:59,685
Blanche!

1310
01:21:59,847 --> 01:22:03,442
- Yes?
- Oh, come on, hon.

1311
01:22:04,367 --> 01:22:07,120
Oh, what pretty, pretty candles.
Don't burn them, Stella.

1312
01:22:07,287 --> 01:22:09,721
- I certainly will.
- No.

1313
01:22:09,887 --> 01:22:11,923
You ought to save them
for baby's birthdays.

1314
01:22:12,087 --> 01:22:14,521
Oh, I hope candles are gonna
glow in his life.

1315
01:22:14,687 --> 01:22:16,882
I hope his eyes are gonna be
like candles...

1316
01:22:17,047 --> 01:22:19,845
...like two blue candles...

1317
01:22:20,087 --> 01:22:21,805
Lining a white cake.

1318
01:22:21,967 --> 01:22:23,161
What poetry.

1319
01:22:28,407 --> 01:22:29,726
I shouldn't have called him.

1320
01:22:29,887 --> 01:22:33,402
Blanche! You know, it's hot in there
with the steam from that bathroom!

1321
01:22:34,967 --> 01:22:38,323
I said I was sorry three times!

1322
01:22:41,607 --> 01:22:43,404
I take hot baths for my nerves.

1323
01:22:43,607 --> 01:22:45,404
Hydrotherapy, they call it.

1324
01:22:45,567 --> 01:22:47,842
You healthy Polack,
without a nerve in your body.

1325
01:22:48,007 --> 01:22:50,760
How can you possibly know
what anxiety feels like?

1326
01:22:50,927 --> 01:22:53,043
I am not a Polack!

1327
01:22:53,207 --> 01:22:56,279
People from Poland are Poles,
they are not Polacks!

1328
01:22:56,447 --> 01:22:58,802
But what I am
is 100 percent American!

1329
01:22:58,967 --> 01:23:02,084
I'm born and raised in the greatest
country on earth and I'm proud of it!

1330
01:23:02,247 --> 01:23:05,239
- And don't you ever call me a Polack!
- That's for me, I'm sure!

1331
01:23:05,407 --> 01:23:07,762
Just keep your seat.
I'm not so sure.

1332
01:23:09,487 --> 01:23:10,966
- Hello.
- <i>Stanley?</i>

1333
01:23:11,247 --> 01:23:13,283
- Yeah, Mac.
- <i>Listen, Stanley...</i>

1334
01:23:14,167 --> 01:23:16,840
Take your hands off me, Stella.
What's the matter with you?

1335
01:23:17,007 --> 01:23:20,522
- Why do you give me that pitying look?
- Will you shut up!

1336
01:23:22,167 --> 01:23:25,204
No, we got a noisy woman in the place.

1337
01:23:25,847 --> 01:23:30,523
I told you I don't want to bowl at Riley's.
I had a little trouble with Riley last week.

1338
01:23:30,687 --> 01:23:34,726
I'm the team captain, ain't I? All right.
Then we're not gonna bowl at Riley's.

1339
01:23:34,887 --> 01:23:37,720
We're gonna bowl at the West Side
or at the Gate, and I'll see you.

1340
01:23:37,887 --> 01:23:39,366
Sister Blanche...

1341
01:23:39,527 --> 01:23:42,519
...I got a little birthday
remembrance for you.

1342
01:23:45,247 --> 01:23:47,363
I hope that you like it.

1343
01:23:55,447 --> 01:23:58,962
- Why, it's a...
- That's a bus ticket back to Auriol.

1344
01:23:59,167 --> 01:24:00,725
Tuesday.

1345
01:24:09,927 --> 01:24:11,565
Blanche.

1346
01:24:17,807 --> 01:24:20,401
You didn't need to do that.

1347
01:24:20,567 --> 01:24:22,922
Don't forget all that I took off of her.

1348
01:24:23,127 --> 01:24:25,721
You didn't need to be so cruel
to someone as alone as she is.

1349
01:24:25,887 --> 01:24:28,526
- A delicate article, she is.
- She is. She was.

1350
01:24:28,687 --> 01:24:30,166
You didn't know Blanche as a girl.

1351
01:24:30,327 --> 01:24:33,125
Nobody, nobody was as tender
and as trusting as she was.

1352
01:24:33,287 --> 01:24:36,563
But people like you abused her
and forced her to change.

1353
01:24:37,007 --> 01:24:39,965
- Do you think you're going bowling now?
- That's right.

1354
01:24:40,487 --> 01:24:42,842
You're not going bowling.
Why did you do this to her?

1355
01:24:43,007 --> 01:24:45,043
- Let go of me.
- I want to know why! Tell me why!

1356
01:24:45,247 --> 01:24:46,441
Hey, cool it!

1357
01:24:46,647 --> 01:24:50,401
Listen, baby, when we first met,
you and me, you thought I was common.

1358
01:24:50,607 --> 01:24:53,201
Well, how right you was.
I was common as dirt.

1359
01:24:53,367 --> 01:24:55,483
You showed me a snapshot
of a place with columns...

1360
01:24:55,687 --> 01:24:58,360
...and I pulled you down off them
columns and you loved it.

1361
01:24:58,527 --> 01:25:00,165
Having them colored lights going.

1362
01:25:00,327 --> 01:25:03,444
And wasn't we happy together?
Wasn't it all okay till she showed here?

1363
01:25:04,607 --> 01:25:08,600
Huh? Wasn't we happy together?
Wasn't it all okay till she showed here?

1364
01:25:08,767 --> 01:25:11,839
Hoity-toity, describing me like a ape.

1365
01:25:17,687 --> 01:25:18,881
Stella?

1366
01:25:23,487 --> 01:25:25,364
What's the matter with you?

1367
01:25:30,007 --> 01:25:32,362
Honey, what's the matter with you?

1368
01:25:39,567 --> 01:25:41,523
Honey, did I hurt you?

1369
01:25:42,847 --> 01:25:44,803
Baby, what is it?

1370
01:25:47,647 --> 01:25:50,207
Take me to the hospital.

1371
01:26:18,127 --> 01:26:20,163
Who is it, please?

1372
01:26:20,367 --> 01:26:23,120
Me. Me, Mitch.

1373
01:26:24,767 --> 01:26:26,280
Mitch.

1374
01:26:35,687 --> 01:26:37,484
Just a minute, please.

1375
01:26:44,847 --> 01:26:47,566
Coming. Coming.

1376
01:26:55,607 --> 01:26:56,801
Hello, Mitch.

1377
01:26:56,967 --> 01:27:00,642
You know, I really shouldn't let you in
after the treatment I received from you.

1378
01:27:01,007 --> 01:27:03,760
So utterly uncavalier.
But, hello, beautiful.

1379
01:27:03,927 --> 01:27:07,044
Oh, my, my, what a cold shoulder.
And what uncouth apparel.

1380
01:27:07,247 --> 01:27:08,566
Why, you haven't even shaved.

1381
01:27:08,727 --> 01:27:11,002
But I forgive you,
because it's a relief to see you.

1382
01:27:11,207 --> 01:27:13,084
You stopped that polka tune
I had in my head.

1383
01:27:13,287 --> 01:27:14,959
Ever get anything caught in your head?

1384
01:27:15,127 --> 01:27:17,846
Of course not, you never get
anything awful caught in your head.

1385
01:27:18,007 --> 01:27:19,599
- We have to have that fan on?
- No.

1386
01:27:19,767 --> 01:27:22,327
- I don't like fans.
- Well, let's turn it off, honey.

1387
01:27:22,487 --> 01:27:23,761
I'm not partial to them.

1388
01:27:23,927 --> 01:27:26,521
I don't know what there is to drink,
I haven't investigated.

1389
01:27:26,687 --> 01:27:29,042
- I don't want Stan's liquor.
- It isn't Stan's!

1390
01:27:29,247 --> 01:27:32,205
Some things on the premises
are actually mine.

1391
01:27:32,447 --> 01:27:33,641
How's your mother?

1392
01:27:34,047 --> 01:27:36,607
- Is your mother well?
- Why?

1393
01:27:37,167 --> 01:27:39,123
Something the matter with you.
But never mind.

1394
01:27:39,287 --> 01:27:43,439
I won't cross-examine the witness, I'll just
pretend I didn't notice anything different.

1395
01:27:44,247 --> 01:27:46,283
It's that music again.

1396
01:27:48,727 --> 01:27:50,365
What music?

1397
01:27:51,727 --> 01:27:54,241
The polka tune they were playing
when Allan...

1398
01:27:55,967 --> 01:27:57,480
Wait.

1399
01:27:58,007 --> 01:27:59,201
There...

1400
01:27:59,567 --> 01:28:01,080
...the shot.

1401
01:28:04,087 --> 01:28:06,521
It always stops after that.

1402
01:28:10,007 --> 01:28:11,360
Yes.

1403
01:28:12,367 --> 01:28:14,164
Now it's stopped.

1404
01:28:16,527 --> 01:28:18,199
Are you boxed out of your mind?

1405
01:28:24,847 --> 01:28:27,566
Oh, I'll go and see what I can
find in the way of...

1406
01:28:27,727 --> 01:28:31,481
By the way, forgive me not being
dressed. I'd practically given you up.

1407
01:28:31,647 --> 01:28:35,003
- Had you forgotten your invitation?
- I wasn't going to see you anymore.

1408
01:28:35,167 --> 01:28:36,839
Wait, I can't hear what you're saying.

1409
01:28:37,007 --> 01:28:38,963
You talk so seldom,
when you do say anything...

1410
01:28:39,127 --> 01:28:41,163
...I don't want to miss
a single syllable of it.

1411
01:28:41,407 --> 01:28:44,126
What am I looking for around here?
Oh, yes. The liquor.

1412
01:28:44,287 --> 01:28:47,279
We've had so much excitement,
I am boxed out of my mind.

1413
01:28:47,447 --> 01:28:48,846
Here's something.

1414
01:28:49,007 --> 01:28:51,123
"Southern Cheer."

1415
01:28:51,287 --> 01:28:53,164
What can that be, I wonder?

1416
01:28:53,807 --> 01:28:56,082
Take your foot off the bed.
It has a clean cover on it.

1417
01:28:56,287 --> 01:28:58,164
You boys wouldn't notice
a thing like that.

1418
01:28:58,327 --> 01:29:02,286
- I've done so much to this place since l...
- Aren't you leaving here pretty soon?

1419
01:29:02,647 --> 01:29:05,081
I wonder if this ought to be
mixed with something.

1420
01:29:06,487 --> 01:29:09,524
It's sweet, terribly sweet.
Why, I believe it's a liqueur.

1421
01:29:09,687 --> 01:29:12,963
Yes, that's what it is, a liqueur.
I don't think you'll like it, but try it.

1422
01:29:13,167 --> 01:29:14,805
- Maybe you will.
- I told you before...

1423
01:29:14,967 --> 01:29:17,003
...I don't want any of his liquor,
and I mean it.

1424
01:29:17,167 --> 01:29:19,601
He says you been lapping it up
all summer like a wildcat.

1425
01:29:19,807 --> 01:29:22,924
I won't descend to the level
of such a cheap accusation to answer...

1426
01:29:23,447 --> 01:29:25,199
What's in your mind?

1427
01:29:25,607 --> 01:29:27,962
- I see something in your eyes.
- It's dark in here.

1428
01:29:28,167 --> 01:29:30,806
I like the dark.
The dark is comforting to me.

1429
01:29:31,087 --> 01:29:33,681
I've never seen you in the light.
That's a fact.

1430
01:29:33,847 --> 01:29:35,724
I've never seen you in the afternoon.

1431
01:29:36,327 --> 01:29:40,161
- I met you at the plant in the afternoon.
- Not on Sunday afternoon!

1432
01:29:40,327 --> 01:29:43,842
You never wanna go out till after 6, then
it's always someplace not lighted much.

1433
01:29:44,007 --> 01:29:46,043
Some obscure meaning in this
I fail to catch.

1434
01:29:46,207 --> 01:29:48,721
What it means is I've never had
a real good look at you.

1435
01:29:48,887 --> 01:29:50,764
- Let's turn the light on.
- Light? What for?

1436
01:29:50,967 --> 01:29:53,162
This one here with
this paper thing on it.

1437
01:29:54,007 --> 01:29:57,886
- What did you want to do that for?
- So I can see you, good and plain.

1438
01:29:58,047 --> 01:30:01,084
- You don't really mean to be insulting.
- No, just realistic.

1439
01:30:01,247 --> 01:30:03,602
- I don't want realism. I want magic.
- Magic.

1440
01:30:03,767 --> 01:30:05,803
Yes, yes, magic.

1441
01:30:06,007 --> 01:30:09,443
I try to give that to people. I do
misrepresent things, I don't tell truth.

1442
01:30:09,607 --> 01:30:13,282
I tell what ought to be truth and if that
is sinful, then let me be punished for it.

1443
01:30:13,447 --> 01:30:15,642
Don't turn the light on!

1444
01:30:23,847 --> 01:30:27,123
Oh, I don't mind you
being older than what I thought...

1445
01:30:28,607 --> 01:30:30,643
...but all the rest of it.

1446
01:30:32,487 --> 01:30:36,719
Why, that pitch about your ideals
being so old-fashioned...

1447
01:30:36,887 --> 01:30:39,606
...and all the malarkey that
you've been dishing out all summer.

1448
01:30:39,767 --> 01:30:43,646
I knew you weren't 16, but I was
fool enough to believe you was straight!

1449
01:30:44,327 --> 01:30:46,841
Who told you I wasn't straight?
My loving brother-in-law?

1450
01:30:47,007 --> 01:30:48,406
- And you believed him?
- No!

1451
01:30:48,727 --> 01:30:52,800
No, I called him a liar at first
and then I checked on the story.

1452
01:30:52,967 --> 01:30:55,481
I talked over long distance
to this merchant in Auriol.

1453
01:30:55,647 --> 01:30:57,603
- Who is this merchant?
- Kiefaber.

1454
01:30:57,767 --> 01:31:00,725
The merchant Kiefaber of Auriol.
I know the man. He whistled at me.

1455
01:31:00,887 --> 01:31:03,321
I put him in his place.
Now he makes up stories about me.

1456
01:31:03,487 --> 01:31:05,443
Didn't you stay at a hotel
called the Flamingo?

1457
01:31:05,647 --> 01:31:08,400
Flamingo? No!

1458
01:31:08,567 --> 01:31:10,683
Tarantula was the name of it.

1459
01:31:10,847 --> 01:31:14,760
- I stayed at a hotel called Tarantula Arms.
- Tarantula Arms?

1460
01:31:14,927 --> 01:31:18,442
Yes, a big spider. That's where
I brought my victims.

1461
01:31:18,647 --> 01:31:19,841
Yes.

1462
01:31:20,007 --> 01:31:24,159
I have had many meetings
with strangers.

1463
01:31:31,447 --> 01:31:33,563
After the death of Allan...

1464
01:31:33,767 --> 01:31:39,603
...meetings with strangers was all I
seemed able to fill my empty heart with.

1465
01:31:40,167 --> 01:31:42,044
I think it was panic, just panic...

1466
01:31:42,207 --> 01:31:45,279
...that drove me from one to another,
searching for some protection.

1467
01:31:45,447 --> 01:31:50,965
Here, there, and then
in the most unlikely places.

1468
01:31:51,447 --> 01:31:56,805
Even, at last, in a 17-year-old boy.
But somebody wrote the superintendent:

1469
01:31:56,967 --> 01:32:00,004
"This woman is morally unfit
for her position."

1470
01:32:00,167 --> 01:32:01,600
True?

1471
01:32:01,767 --> 01:32:03,280
Yes.

1472
01:32:03,447 --> 01:32:05,483
Unfit somehow, anyway.

1473
01:32:05,647 --> 01:32:08,639
So I came here.
There was nowhere else I could go.

1474
01:32:08,807 --> 01:32:11,401
I was played out.
You know what played out is?

1475
01:32:11,567 --> 01:32:14,400
My youth was gone up the waterspout.

1476
01:32:14,567 --> 01:32:16,080
Then I met you.

1477
01:32:16,247 --> 01:32:18,124
You said you needed someone.

1478
01:32:18,327 --> 01:32:20,522
Well, I needed someone too.

1479
01:32:20,727 --> 01:32:22,524
I thanked God for you.

1480
01:32:22,727 --> 01:32:24,683
You seemed gentle.

1481
01:32:24,887 --> 01:32:26,081
A cleft...

1482
01:32:26,247 --> 01:32:29,842
...in the rock of the world
that I could hide in.

1483
01:32:31,407 --> 01:32:33,967
But I suppose I was asking...

1484
01:32:34,127 --> 01:32:36,960
...hoping too much.

1485
01:32:38,007 --> 01:32:39,281
Kiefaber...

1486
01:32:39,447 --> 01:32:44,202
...Harris and Shaw have tied an old tin
can to the tail of the kite.

1487
01:32:45,007 --> 01:32:46,440
I thought you were straight.

1488
01:32:48,287 --> 01:32:50,084
Straight?

1489
01:32:50,527 --> 01:32:52,324
What's straight?

1490
01:32:52,727 --> 01:32:55,844
A line can be straight, or a street...

1491
01:32:56,247 --> 01:32:58,841
...but the heart of a human being?

1492
01:33:01,087 --> 01:33:03,885
- You lied to me, Blanche.
- Don't say I lied to you.

1493
01:33:04,047 --> 01:33:08,040
- Lies! Lies! Inside and out, all lies!
- Never inside.

1494
01:33:08,207 --> 01:33:10,641
I never lied in my heart!

1495
01:33:15,367 --> 01:33:17,164
What?

1496
01:33:19,727 --> 01:33:21,683
From outside.

1497
01:33:29,327 --> 01:33:31,602
Flowers.
Flowers for the dead.

1498
01:33:34,807 --> 01:33:36,320
No.

1499
01:33:36,727 --> 01:33:38,126
No.

1500
01:33:38,847 --> 01:33:40,326
Not now.

1501
01:33:40,727 --> 01:33:42,319
Not now.

1502
01:33:46,967 --> 01:33:51,404
I lived in a house where dying
old women remembered their dead men.

1503
01:33:51,567 --> 01:33:53,159
Crumble, then fade.

1504
01:33:53,327 --> 01:33:55,443
Regrets, recriminations.

1505
01:33:55,607 --> 01:33:58,599
"If you'd done this,
it wouldn't have cost me that."

1506
01:33:58,767 --> 01:34:00,120
Legacies...

1507
01:34:00,287 --> 01:34:01,481
...and other things...

1508
01:34:01,647 --> 01:34:03,763
...such as bloodstained pillowslips.

1509
01:34:05,207 --> 01:34:07,004
I used to sit here...

1510
01:34:07,167 --> 01:34:08,361
...and she used to sit there.

1511
01:34:09,047 --> 01:34:12,119
And death was as close as you are.

1512
01:34:12,727 --> 01:34:14,240
Death.

1513
01:34:14,647 --> 01:34:17,207
The opposite is desire.

1514
01:34:17,367 --> 01:34:18,959
So how could you wonder?

1515
01:34:19,127 --> 01:34:22,005
How could you possibly wonder?

1516
01:34:24,727 --> 01:34:28,402
Not far from Belle Reve,
before we lost Belle Reve...

1517
01:34:28,567 --> 01:34:32,003
...was a camp
where they trained young soldiers.

1518
01:34:32,247 --> 01:34:35,284
On Saturday nights,
they would go in town to get drunk.

1519
01:34:35,447 --> 01:34:39,565
And on the way back, they would
stagger onto my lawn and call:

1520
01:34:40,167 --> 01:34:42,442
"Blanche."

1521
01:34:43,727 --> 01:34:45,843
"Blanche."

1522
01:35:01,367 --> 01:35:03,483
What do you want?

1523
01:35:10,807 --> 01:35:13,002
Marry me, Mitch.

1524
01:35:14,047 --> 01:35:16,402
No, I don't think
I want to marry you anymore.

1525
01:35:17,527 --> 01:35:19,119
No?

1526
01:35:19,607 --> 01:35:22,963
No. You're not clean enough
to bring in the house with my mo...

1527
01:35:23,167 --> 01:35:25,601
Go, then!

1528
01:35:27,647 --> 01:35:29,319
Get out of here.

1529
01:35:29,487 --> 01:35:32,240
Quick, before I start screaming.

1530
01:35:32,807 --> 01:35:35,924
Get out of here quick,
before I start screaming!

1531
01:35:36,167 --> 01:35:38,442
Scream! Scream!

1532
01:35:50,687 --> 01:35:52,564
Are you all right, lady?

1533
01:35:54,887 --> 01:35:58,163
What's the matter, lady?
<i>What's the matter, lady?</i>

1534
01:36:09,527 --> 01:36:11,961
- She must be drunk.
- Somebody better get a policeman.

1535
01:36:12,127 --> 01:36:13,924
There's a cop now.

1536
01:36:15,127 --> 01:36:17,322
- What's the matter? What happened?
- I don't know.

1537
01:36:30,207 --> 01:36:32,243
It's a police officer. Open up.

1538
01:36:34,487 --> 01:36:36,364
Open up in there.

1539
01:36:37,207 --> 01:36:39,323
It's a police officer, open up.

1540
01:36:40,087 --> 01:36:42,123
What's the matter? Are you hurt, lady?

1541
01:36:42,807 --> 01:36:44,479
Are you all right, lady?

1542
01:36:44,647 --> 01:36:46,444
Yes. Go away.

1543
01:36:48,247 --> 01:36:50,203
- Go on.
- Are you hurt?

1544
01:36:50,487 --> 01:36:52,842
- Are you all right?
- I'll be good.

1545
01:36:53,207 --> 01:36:55,402
It's all right. Let's break it up.

1546
01:37:00,527 --> 01:37:02,119
I'll be good.

1547
01:37:05,407 --> 01:37:08,319
I'll be good. I'll be good.

1548
01:37:11,007 --> 01:37:15,842
Oh, no, my gracious. What a thing.

1549
01:37:16,527 --> 01:37:20,281
How about taking a swim,
a moonlight swim at the old rock quarry?

1550
01:37:20,487 --> 01:37:22,523
That's if anyone's sober enough
to drive a car.

1551
01:37:22,727 --> 01:37:25,161
The best way in the world
to stop your head from buzzing.

1552
01:37:25,367 --> 01:37:28,040
Only you have to be careful to dive
where the deep pool is.

1553
01:37:28,207 --> 01:37:32,200
If you hit a rock, you won't come up
till tomorrow.

1554
01:37:33,247 --> 01:37:37,001
My goodness. They're playing
"Goodnight, Ladies."

1555
01:37:38,647 --> 01:37:41,559
May I rest my weary head
on your shoulder?

1556
01:37:41,727 --> 01:37:43,240
It's so...

1557
01:37:43,407 --> 01:37:45,045
...comforting.

1558
01:37:55,607 --> 01:37:57,279
Hi, Blanche.

1559
01:38:15,127 --> 01:38:18,642
- How's my sister?
- She's doing okay.

1560
01:38:20,407 --> 01:38:21,886
How's the baby?

1561
01:38:22,407 --> 01:38:26,161
The baby won't come till tomorrow,
so they told me to get a little shuteye.

1562
01:38:28,927 --> 01:38:30,440
Does that mean...

1563
01:38:30,727 --> 01:38:32,922
...we are to be alone in here?

1564
01:38:33,607 --> 01:38:35,723
Yeah, it's just you and me, Blanche.

1565
01:38:36,807 --> 01:38:39,765
Hey, what do you got
them fine feathers on for?

1566
01:38:41,207 --> 01:38:45,120
That's right.
You left before my wire came.

1567
01:38:45,727 --> 01:38:47,479
What, you got a wire?

1568
01:38:48,047 --> 01:38:51,119
I received a telegram
from an old admirer of mine.

1569
01:38:51,287 --> 01:38:55,644
- Anything good?
- I think so. An invitation.

1570
01:38:56,287 --> 01:38:57,845
What to?

1571
01:38:59,727 --> 01:39:02,764
A cruise of the Caribbean on a yacht.

1572
01:39:03,607 --> 01:39:05,404
Well, what do you know?

1573
01:39:05,887 --> 01:39:09,402
I was never so surprised in my life.
It came like a bolt from the blue.

1574
01:39:10,127 --> 01:39:12,083
Who'd you say it was from?

1575
01:39:13,847 --> 01:39:15,439
An old beau of mine.

1576
01:39:16,927 --> 01:39:19,282
Oh, the one that give you
the white fox fur pieces.

1577
01:39:19,847 --> 01:39:21,246
Shep Huntleigh.

1578
01:39:21,407 --> 01:39:23,602
I wore his ATO pin
my last year in college.

1579
01:39:23,807 --> 01:39:26,241
I hadn't seen him for a while,
then just now this wire...

1580
01:39:26,447 --> 01:39:29,359
...inviting me on a cruise of the
Caribbean. The problem is clothes.

1581
01:39:29,527 --> 01:39:32,644
I tore into my trunk to see what I had
that was suitable for the tropics.

1582
01:39:32,847 --> 01:39:35,361
And you come up
with a gorgeous diamond tiara.

1583
01:39:35,527 --> 01:39:37,643
This old relic? It's only rhinestones.

1584
01:39:38,487 --> 01:39:40,523
Oh, I thought it was
Tiffany's diamonds.

1585
01:39:40,727 --> 01:39:43,685
Well, anyhow,
I shall be entertained in style.

1586
01:39:43,847 --> 01:39:46,919
Well, it just goes to show you,
Blanche, you never know what's coming.

1587
01:39:47,247 --> 01:39:49,283
When I thought my luck
was beginning to fail me.

1588
01:39:49,487 --> 01:39:52,285
Into the picture
pops this Miami millionaire.

1589
01:39:52,607 --> 01:39:54,882
This man is not from Miami.
This man is from Dallas.

1590
01:39:55,087 --> 01:39:57,521
Just so he's from somewhere.

1591
01:39:57,887 --> 01:40:00,606
Close the curtains
before you undress any further.

1592
01:40:00,767 --> 01:40:03,327
No, this is all
I'm gonna undress right now.

1593
01:40:05,047 --> 01:40:07,163
Hey, Blanche,
you seen the bottle opener?

1594
01:40:08,727 --> 01:40:12,640
I used to have a cousin who could open
a bottle of beer with his teeth.

1595
01:40:12,807 --> 01:40:17,039
And that was all he could do.
He was just a human bottle-opener.

1596
01:40:18,007 --> 01:40:22,125
Then one time at a wedding party,
he broke his front teeth right off.

1597
01:40:22,727 --> 01:40:25,525
And then after that,
he was so ashamed of himself...

1598
01:40:25,687 --> 01:40:28,963
...that he used to sneak out of the house
when company came.

1599
01:40:29,687 --> 01:40:31,723
Rain from heaven.

1600
01:40:39,567 --> 01:40:42,923
What do you say, Blanche? You want to
bury the hatchet and make a loving cup?

1601
01:40:43,647 --> 01:40:45,046
No. No, thank you.

1602
01:40:46,207 --> 01:40:48,641
- Why don't you get with it?
- What are you doing in here?

1603
01:40:48,847 --> 01:40:51,486
Hey, wait a second.
I want to show you something.

1604
01:40:51,887 --> 01:40:54,321
Here's something I always break out
on special occasions:

1605
01:40:54,527 --> 01:40:56,279
Silk pajamas I wore
on my wedding night.

1606
01:40:56,447 --> 01:40:58,802
When they call on that phone
and say, "You got a son"...

1607
01:40:58,967 --> 01:41:01,765
...I'm gonna rip them off
and wave them like a flag!

1608
01:41:01,927 --> 01:41:03,883
I guess we're both entitled
to put on a dog.

1609
01:41:04,087 --> 01:41:07,204
You're having an oil millionaire
and I'm having the baby.

1610
01:41:08,487 --> 01:41:12,082
When I think of how divine it'll be to
have such a thing as privacy once more...

1611
01:41:12,247 --> 01:41:13,839
...I could weep with joy.

1612
01:41:14,127 --> 01:41:16,925
This millionaire isn't gonna interfere
with your privacy none?

1613
01:41:17,527 --> 01:41:19,722
It won't be the sort of thing
you have in mind.

1614
01:41:19,887 --> 01:41:21,684
This man is a gentleman.
He respects me.

1615
01:41:21,967 --> 01:41:23,446
What he wants is my companionship.

1616
01:41:23,607 --> 01:41:25,882
Having great wealth
sometimes makes people lonely.

1617
01:41:26,087 --> 01:41:28,521
A cultivated woman,
a woman of breeding and intelligence...

1618
01:41:28,727 --> 01:41:32,003
...can enrich a man's life immeasurably.
I have those things to offer.

1619
01:41:32,167 --> 01:41:34,362
And time doesn't take them away.

1620
01:41:34,567 --> 01:41:39,243
Physical beauty is passing,
a transitory possession.

1621
01:41:39,407 --> 01:41:44,162
But beauty of the mind, richness
of the spirit, tenderness of the heart...

1622
01:41:44,327 --> 01:41:50,323
I have all those things... . aren't taken
away, but grow, increase with the years.

1623
01:41:53,807 --> 01:41:57,163
Strange that I should be called
a destitute woman...

1624
01:41:57,327 --> 01:42:01,206
...when I have all these treasures
locked in my heart.

1625
01:42:02,167 --> 01:42:05,682
I think of myself as a very,
very rich woman.

1626
01:42:05,847 --> 01:42:09,522
But I have been foolish,
casting my pearls before...

1627
01:42:09,727 --> 01:42:10,762
Swine, huh?

1628
01:42:11,447 --> 01:42:13,802
Yes. Swine.

1629
01:42:14,087 --> 01:42:17,363
And I'm thinking not only of you but
of Mr. Mitchell. He came here tonight.

1630
01:42:17,527 --> 01:42:20,963
He dared to come in his work clothes to
repeat slander, vicious stories from you.

1631
01:42:21,167 --> 01:42:22,919
I gave him his walking papers.

1632
01:42:23,847 --> 01:42:28,204
But then he returned. He returned with
a box of roses to beg my forgiveness.

1633
01:42:28,367 --> 01:42:30,483
He implored my forgiveness.

1634
01:42:30,927 --> 01:42:34,203
But some things are not forgivable.

1635
01:42:35,887 --> 01:42:39,641
Deliberate cruelty is not forgivable!

1636
01:42:39,847 --> 01:42:42,486
It is one unforgivable thing,
in my opinion...

1637
01:42:42,647 --> 01:42:44,842
...and the one thing
of which I have never...

1638
01:42:45,047 --> 01:42:46,560
...never been guilty.

1639
01:42:46,727 --> 01:42:49,844
So I said to him, " Thank you.

1640
01:42:50,007 --> 01:42:53,204
It was foolish of me to think that
we could adapt ourselves to each other.

1641
01:42:53,407 --> 01:42:56,683
Our ways of life are too different,
our backgrounds are incompatible.

1642
01:42:57,007 --> 01:43:02,525
So farewell, my friend,
and let there be no hard feelings."

1643
01:43:19,287 --> 01:43:22,643
Was this before or after
you got the telegram?

1644
01:43:23,247 --> 01:43:26,205
Telegram? What telegram?

1645
01:43:27,647 --> 01:43:30,081
- As a matter of fact, my wire...
- As a matter of fact...

1646
01:43:30,247 --> 01:43:32,522
...there wasn't no wire at all.

1647
01:43:35,767 --> 01:43:38,201
And there isn't no millionaire.

1648
01:43:39,647 --> 01:43:43,765
And Mitch didn't come in here with
roses, because I know where he is.

1649
01:43:43,927 --> 01:43:48,603
And there isn't a thing but imagination
and lies and deceit and tricks.

1650
01:43:48,807 --> 01:43:50,445
And look at yourself.

1651
01:43:50,607 --> 01:43:53,519
Take a look at yourself here,
in a worn-out Mardi Gras outfit.

1652
01:43:53,687 --> 01:43:57,362
Rented for 50 cents from some
rag picker with a crazy crown on.

1653
01:43:57,527 --> 01:43:59,563
What kind of a queen
do you think you are?

1654
01:43:59,927 --> 01:44:02,202
You know that I've been on to you
from the start...

1655
01:44:02,407 --> 01:44:05,205
...and not once did you pull the wool
over this boy's eyes.

1656
01:44:05,487 --> 01:44:08,923
You come here and sprinkle the place
with powder and you spray perfume...

1657
01:44:09,087 --> 01:44:11,123
...and stick a paper lantern
over the light bulb.

1658
01:44:11,327 --> 01:44:13,363
And lo and behold,
place is turned into Egypt...

1659
01:44:13,527 --> 01:44:16,200
...and you're the queen of the Nile,
sitting on your throne...

1660
01:44:16,367 --> 01:44:18,483
...swilling down my liquor.
You know what I say?

1661
01:44:21,727 --> 01:44:22,921
You hear me?

1662
01:45:01,327 --> 01:45:02,885
Flowers.

1663
01:45:06,327 --> 01:45:07,521
No.

1664
01:45:07,767 --> 01:45:08,802
No.

1665
01:45:09,047 --> 01:45:10,685
Not now.

1666
01:45:21,087 --> 01:45:24,602
- <i>Operator.</i>
- What happened to long distance?

1667
01:45:24,767 --> 01:45:27,201
Never mind long distance.
Get me Western Union.

1668
01:45:27,407 --> 01:45:31,002
Western Union? Hear me?
Take down this message:

1669
01:45:31,207 --> 01:45:33,084
"Desperate, desperate circumstances.

1670
01:45:33,247 --> 01:45:37,001
Caught in a trap. Help me.
Caught in a trap."

1671
01:45:37,167 --> 01:45:42,605
<i>Hello? Operator. I can give you</i>
<i>Western Union now.</i>

1672
01:45:47,647 --> 01:45:49,365
<i>Western Union.</i>

1673
01:45:51,487 --> 01:45:53,921
<i>Hello? Western Union.</i>

1674
01:45:54,487 --> 01:45:57,240
<i>Hello? Western Union.</i>

1675
01:45:58,887 --> 01:46:00,923
<i>This is Western Union.</i>

1676
01:46:02,127 --> 01:46:03,480
<i>Hello.</i>

1677
01:46:04,047 --> 01:46:08,245
- You left the phone off the hook.
- <i>This is Western Union.</i>

1678
01:46:17,727 --> 01:46:19,126
Let me...

1679
01:46:19,567 --> 01:46:21,683
Let me get by you.

1680
01:46:22,407 --> 01:46:24,523
You wanna get by me? Go ahead.

1681
01:46:26,487 --> 01:46:28,284
Stand over there.

1682
01:46:30,327 --> 01:46:32,522
You got plenty of room
to get by me now.

1683
01:46:34,247 --> 01:46:37,842
I've got to get out. Somehow.

1684
01:46:39,447 --> 01:46:41,881
You think I'm gonna
interfere with you?

1685
01:46:55,087 --> 01:46:57,806
You know, maybe you won't be bad
to interfere with.

1686
01:47:00,087 --> 01:47:03,682
Stand back. Don't you come
toward me another step, or I'll...

1687
01:47:03,847 --> 01:47:07,362
- You'll what?
- Some awful thing will happen. It will!

1688
01:47:09,527 --> 01:47:11,040
What are you putting on now?

1689
01:47:19,607 --> 01:47:25,204
I warn you. Don't. I'm in danger!

1690
01:47:30,967 --> 01:47:32,605
What did you do that for?

1691
01:47:33,687 --> 01:47:36,884
So I could twist the broken end
in your face.

1692
01:47:37,687 --> 01:47:41,839
- I bet you would do that.
- I would. I will, if you...

1693
01:47:47,327 --> 01:47:49,761
You wanna have
a little roughhouse, huh?

1694
01:47:52,087 --> 01:47:53,964
All right, let's have a little roughhouse.

1695
01:47:59,527 --> 01:48:04,726
Tiger, tiger. Drop that bottle top.
Drop it!

1696
01:48:17,607 --> 01:48:20,246
Oh, inside straight, man!

1697
01:48:22,327 --> 01:48:23,601
Try it in English, mustache.

1698
01:48:23,767 --> 01:48:26,486
- I'm cursing your rotten luck.
- You know what luck is?

1699
01:48:26,647 --> 01:48:28,683
Luck is believing you're lucky,
that's all.

1700
01:48:28,887 --> 01:48:32,084
Take at Salerno. I believed I was lucky.
I figured that four out of five...

1701
01:48:32,247 --> 01:48:34,442
...wasn't gonna get through
but I would, and I did.

1702
01:48:34,607 --> 01:48:37,804
I stick that down as a rule: To hold
the front position in this rat race...

1703
01:48:37,967 --> 01:48:39,446
...you gotta believe you're lucky.

1704
01:48:39,607 --> 01:48:43,361
- You... You... You brag... Brag bull!
- What's the matter with you?

1705
01:48:43,567 --> 01:48:47,162
I always said men was callous things
with no feeling, but this beats anything.

1706
01:48:47,367 --> 01:48:51,201
- Sitting there making pigs of yourselves.
- What's the matter with her?

1707
01:48:52,367 --> 01:48:53,846
Come on, deal.

1708
01:48:54,447 --> 01:48:56,802
- <i>Blanche?</i>
- Bathing.

1709
01:48:57,087 --> 01:48:58,645
How's my baby?

1710
01:48:58,807 --> 01:49:02,243
Sleeping like a little angel.
I brought you some grapes.

1711
01:49:03,247 --> 01:49:05,681
- How is she?
- She wouldn't eat anything.

1712
01:49:05,887 --> 01:49:09,084
I keep telling her we made arrangements
for her to rest in the country.

1713
01:49:09,367 --> 01:49:12,359
She's got it all mixed-up in her mind
about a cruise to the islands...

1714
01:49:12,527 --> 01:49:14,563
...with Shep Huntleigh, an old beau...
- Stella?

1715
01:49:14,727 --> 01:49:17,002
- Yes?
- lf anyone calls while I'm bathing...

1716
01:49:17,167 --> 01:49:19,362
...take the number,
tell them I'll call right back.

1717
01:49:19,527 --> 01:49:21,085
- Yes, Blanche.
- Oh, and Stella!

1718
01:49:21,327 --> 01:49:24,763
The... The cool yellow silk, the boucl,
see if it's crushed.

1719
01:49:25,127 --> 01:49:28,483
If it's not too crushed, I'll wear it.
And on the lapel...

1720
01:49:28,887 --> 01:49:32,163
...that silver and turquoise pin
in the shape of a seahorse.

1721
01:49:32,327 --> 01:49:35,205
You'll find it in the heart-shaped box
I keep my accessories in.

1722
01:49:35,367 --> 01:49:39,406
Oh, and Stella, see if you can locate
a bunch of artificial...

1723
01:49:40,927 --> 01:49:45,239
...violets in that box. I'll wear it with
the seahorse on the lapel of the jacket.

1724
01:49:57,727 --> 01:49:59,763
I just don't know
if I've done the right thing.

1725
01:49:59,967 --> 01:50:01,400
What else could you do?

1726
01:50:01,567 --> 01:50:04,240
I couldn't believe her story
and go on living with Stanley.

1727
01:50:04,407 --> 01:50:08,161
Don't you never believe it.
You gotta keep on going, baby.

1728
01:50:08,367 --> 01:50:11,165
No matter what happens,
we all gotta keep on going.

1729
01:50:11,327 --> 01:50:13,045
- Stella?
- Yes, Blanche?

1730
01:50:13,287 --> 01:50:16,245
- Is the coast clear?
- Yes, honey.

1731
01:50:16,407 --> 01:50:18,762
Close the curtains before I come out.

1732
01:50:18,967 --> 01:50:21,242
Tell her how well she's looking.

1733
01:50:23,687 --> 01:50:25,643
They're closed, honey.

1734
01:50:32,247 --> 01:50:33,680
I just washed my hair.

1735
01:50:34,407 --> 01:50:38,082
- Oh, did you?
- I'm not sure I got all the soap out.

1736
01:50:38,287 --> 01:50:40,721
- Such fine hair.
- That's the problem.

1737
01:50:40,927 --> 01:50:43,441
- Did I get a call?
- Who from?

1738
01:50:43,607 --> 01:50:47,282
- Shep Huntleigh.
- No, honey, not yet.

1739
01:50:47,447 --> 01:50:49,881
- Strange.
- Come on, Mitch.

1740
01:50:56,647 --> 01:50:58,842
<i>Mitch?</i>

1741
01:51:04,767 --> 01:51:06,644
What's happened here?

1742
01:51:07,007 --> 01:51:08,963
I want an explanation
of what's happened here!

1743
01:51:09,167 --> 01:51:10,839
- Hush, please, Blanche.
- Honey...

1744
01:51:11,767 --> 01:51:14,122
What are you two
looking at me like that for?

1745
01:51:14,327 --> 01:51:16,204
Is there something wrong with me?

1746
01:51:16,367 --> 01:51:18,642
You look wonderful, Blanche.
Don't she look wonderful?

1747
01:51:18,847 --> 01:51:22,123
- I understand you're going on a trip.
- Yes.

1748
01:51:22,287 --> 01:51:24,642
Yes. Blanche is.
She's going on a vacation.

1749
01:51:24,807 --> 01:51:26,763
I'm green with envy.

1750
01:51:28,327 --> 01:51:30,887
Help me, you two.
Help me get dressed.

1751
01:51:31,047 --> 01:51:34,323
- Is this what you wanted?
- Yes, that'll do.

1752
01:51:34,487 --> 01:51:37,081
I'm anxious to get out of this place.
This place is a trap.

1753
01:51:37,247 --> 01:51:39,807
- Such a pretty lavender jacket.
- It's lilac-colored.

1754
01:51:39,967 --> 01:51:42,879
You're both of you wrong.
It's Della Robbia blue.

1755
01:51:43,047 --> 01:51:44,799
Are these grapes washed?

1756
01:51:44,967 --> 01:51:47,720
- Washed, I said. Are they washed?
- From the French Market.

1757
01:51:47,887 --> 01:51:50,321
That doesn't mean to say
they've been washed.

1758
01:51:54,127 --> 01:51:57,324
The cathedral chimes.
They're the only...

1759
01:51:58,247 --> 01:52:00,602
...clean thing in the Quarter.

1760
01:52:01,967 --> 01:52:04,925
I'm going now. I'm ready to go.

1761
01:52:05,767 --> 01:52:07,803
Wait, Blanche!

1762
01:52:08,567 --> 01:52:11,161
Must we pass in front of those men?

1763
01:52:11,327 --> 01:52:13,363
Why don't you wait here
till that game breaks up.

1764
01:52:13,527 --> 01:52:15,279
Yes, honey, sit down.

1765
01:52:21,607 --> 01:52:23,165
Tell them to wait outside.

1766
01:52:24,527 --> 01:52:28,202
Would you mind waiting outside just a
couple of seconds? They'll be right out.

1767
01:52:38,287 --> 01:52:40,642
Someone is calling for Blanche.

1768
01:52:41,847 --> 01:52:43,883
It is for me, then.

1769
01:52:44,087 --> 01:52:47,079
Is it the gentleman
I was expecting from Dallas?

1770
01:52:47,247 --> 01:52:48,441
Yes.

1771
01:52:48,607 --> 01:52:50,882
Yes, honey, I believe it is.

1772
01:52:54,287 --> 01:52:56,721
I'm not quite ready.

1773
01:52:58,327 --> 01:53:00,522
Ask him to wait outside.

1774
01:53:02,087 --> 01:53:03,281
Everything packed?

1775
01:53:03,847 --> 01:53:05,041
Stanley.

1776
01:53:05,407 --> 01:53:06,601
She'll be out in a minute.

1777
01:53:09,247 --> 01:53:12,125
- They're waiting outside the house.
- "They"?

1778
01:53:12,887 --> 01:53:14,479
Who's "they"?

1779
01:53:16,247 --> 01:53:17,566
There's a lady with him.

1780
01:53:18,887 --> 01:53:21,799
I can't imagine who this lady can be.

1781
01:53:22,127 --> 01:53:23,606
How is she dressed?

1782
01:53:25,927 --> 01:53:28,646
Just a plain tailored outfit.

1783
01:53:32,087 --> 01:53:34,043
Possibly she...?

1784
01:53:42,407 --> 01:53:43,999
Shall we go now, Blanche?

1785
01:53:57,487 --> 01:54:01,799
- Must we go through that room?
- I'll go with you.

1786
01:54:04,087 --> 01:54:07,079
- How do I look?
- Lovely.

1787
01:54:07,487 --> 01:54:09,079
Lovely.

1788
01:54:18,007 --> 01:54:22,444
Please don't get up.
I'm only passing through.

1789
01:54:31,007 --> 01:54:32,406
You...

1790
01:54:32,927 --> 01:54:34,645
...are not the gentleman...

1791
01:54:35,207 --> 01:54:36,925
...I was expecting.

1792
01:54:38,687 --> 01:54:41,042
This man isn't Shep Huntleigh!

1793
01:54:49,407 --> 01:54:50,886
You forget something, Blanche?

1794
01:54:53,367 --> 01:54:57,406
Yes. Yes, I forgot something.

1795
01:54:58,807 --> 01:55:00,559
What are they gonna do to her?

1796
01:55:00,727 --> 01:55:02,763
Don't let them hurt her.

1797
01:55:03,607 --> 01:55:05,882
- What are they gonna do to her?
- Honey...

1798
01:55:08,407 --> 01:55:10,204
Hello, Blanche.

1799
01:55:17,687 --> 01:55:19,723
She says she forgot something.

1800
01:55:20,487 --> 01:55:22,125
That's all right.

1801
01:55:24,367 --> 01:55:26,642
Well, what did you forget, Blanche?

1802
01:55:27,647 --> 01:55:31,799
- It don't matter. We can pick it up later.
- We'll send it along with your trunk.

1803
01:55:36,487 --> 01:55:38,364
I don't know you.

1804
01:55:38,567 --> 01:55:40,523
I don't know you.

1805
01:55:40,727 --> 01:55:43,844
- I want to be left alone, please!
- Now, Blanche...

1806
01:55:46,487 --> 01:55:49,763
Blanche, you left nothing here
but spilt talcum and old perfume bottles.

1807
01:55:50,487 --> 01:55:54,162
Unless it's the paper lantern you want to
take with you. You want the lantern?

1808
01:56:12,087 --> 01:56:14,362
You done this to her.

1809
01:56:14,687 --> 01:56:17,963
- Come on, stop it.
- Stop it, will you!

1810
01:56:18,167 --> 01:56:20,522
He did this to her, I know...

1811
01:56:20,727 --> 01:56:22,524
He must be nuts.

1812
01:56:28,207 --> 01:56:29,606
What are you looking at?

1813
01:56:29,767 --> 01:56:31,723
I never once touched her.

1814
01:56:35,807 --> 01:56:39,800
These fingernails have to be trimmed.
Jacket, doctor?

1815
01:56:40,207 --> 01:56:42,641
Not unless necessary.

1816
01:56:43,647 --> 01:56:45,046
Miss DuBois.

1817
01:57:02,047 --> 01:57:03,605
Please...

1818
01:57:03,767 --> 01:57:06,122
It won't be necessary.

1819
01:57:07,487 --> 01:57:09,284
Ask her...

1820
01:57:09,487 --> 01:57:11,842
...to let go of me.

1821
01:57:12,287 --> 01:57:15,120
Yes. Let go.

1822
01:57:48,687 --> 01:57:50,564
Whoever you are...

1823
01:57:50,847 --> 01:57:53,964
...I have always depended
on the kindness...

1824
01:57:54,407 --> 01:57:56,204
...of strangers.

1825
01:58:22,887 --> 01:58:24,639
- Blanche.
- Come on, honey.

1826
01:58:24,807 --> 01:58:27,924
Don't you touch me.
Don't you ever touch me again.

1827
01:58:50,767 --> 01:58:52,519
Stella!

1828
01:58:55,367 --> 01:58:57,323
Come on, Stella.

1829
01:58:57,567 --> 01:59:02,083
No, I'm not. I'm not going back
in there again. Not this time.

1830
01:59:02,247 --> 01:59:04,363
Never going back. Never.

1831
01:59:04,527 --> 01:59:06,563
Hey, Stella!

1832
01:59:07,967 --> 01:59:11,403
Hey, Stella!

